INSERT INTO `gre__item` (`id`, `cid`, `md5sum`, `guid`, `added`, `title`, `url`, `enclosure`, `description`, `unread`, `pubdate`, `author`) VALUES (1,1,'c9aaabadc47b6f558f967ab8c4808056','http://techcrunch.com/?p=528485','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Smart Education: How Lynda.com Hit $70M In Revenue Without A Penny From Investors','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/OpMvB4mtzBA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/lynda_com_logo.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"lynda_com_logo\" />Content companies have struggled to monetize on the Web, and there has been plenty of debate over the effectiveness of paywalls. What\'s more, tech startups really can\'t seem to rush fast enough into the hands of angel investors or venture capitalists. That\'s why, as a digital content company that has been around for years and has yet to take a penny of outside investment, <a href=\"http://www.lynda.com/\">Lynda.com</a> has such relevance in today\'s landscape. \n\nWhile it didn\'t happen over night, Lynda.com has been able to build a paying customer base of over 1 million, outshining every major newspaper, and its traffic is on the rise. Using a passion for education, industry experience, knowledge of what is important to its customers, and focus on product-before-profit, co-founders and married couple Lynda Weinman and Bruce Heavin have turned $20K of their own investment into a platform that produced $70 million in revenue in 2011. \n',1,'2012-05-03 17:51:06','Rip Empson'),(2,1,'e9c4d35eb03e9074175e9bfed1f48795','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545898','2012-05-03 18:12:06','LinkedInÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Mobile Future: 22 Percent Of Visitors Are Mobile, In-Stream Ads Coming?','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/1oexpJwTtnI/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/linkedin-mobile.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"linkedin mobile\" />During the conference call this afternoon for their <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/05/03/linkedin-beats-the-street-q1-revenue-up-101-percent-to-188-5m-net-income-up-140-percent/\">first quarter earnings</a>, LinkedIn executives boasted about the impressive mobile growth they\'re seeing. In the last week of March, the company says mobile accounted for 22 percent of unique visitors, up 8 percent from the same period last year. \n\nAnd although he wouldn\'t share any numbers, CEO Jeff Weiner said adoption of <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/25/finally-professional-social-network-linkedin-gives-users-an-ipad-app/\">the recently-launched iPad app</a> has exceeded the company\'s \"aggressive\" expectations. Weiner mentioned the iPad app again when asked about the areas where the company is strongest right now.',1,'2012-05-03 16:58:31','Anthony Ha'),(3,1,'29723deaaefd9f490924d31c750f60c8','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545831','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Brightcove Reports Q1 Net Loss Of $4.3 Million, Revenue Up 53% to $19.9 Million','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/ek7l7u3E0MA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/02/brightcove.png?w=100&amp;h=60&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"brightcove\" />Video platform <a href=\"http://brightcove.com\">Brightcove</a> just <a href=\"http://investor.brightcove.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=670256\">released</a> its first earnings report after going public in March. Brightcove posted a net loss of $4.3 million - that\'s down from $5.8 million last quarter. The company\'s revenue for the first financial quarter of 2012 was $19.9 million, an increase of 53% compared to the first quarter of 2011 when the company made $13.1 million. Non-GAAP net loss per share was $0.17. Analysts expected a loss of $0.16 per share.\n\nBrightcove\'s gross profit for the first quarter was $13.6 million (up 56% from $8.7 million in Q1 2011). Non-GAAP loss from operations was $2.3 million for the first quarter of 2012, an improvement compared to a non-GAAP loss of $3.4 million during the first quarter of 2011. Brightcove also announced that it had 4,254 customers at the end of the quarter. That\'s up 49% compared to Q1 2011.',1,'2012-05-03 16:44:29','Frederic Lardinois'),(4,1,'80218c6a73f52172b04fd124b8bb92ad','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545644','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Krossover Makes Athletes, Coaches Smarter With Business Intelligence For Sports','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/hlRTEe10iMA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/video-breakdown.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"video-breakdown\" />Anyone who\'s played competitive sports knows how important stats, analysis, and post-game film are. They\'re an excellent way to improve both personally and on a team level, yet it usually takes a dedicated staff to push out rich, thorough analysis. \n\nLuckily, a new startup called <a href=\"http://www.krossover.com/index.php\">Krossover</a> is ready to help solve that problem. \n\nThey call themselves \"business intelligence for sports,\" offering youth, amateur, highschool and college sports teams fully indexed game footage within 12-36 hours of uploading. This includes searchable film, box scores, shot charts and drive charts, and thorough analytical reports for every player on the team. ',1,'2012-05-03 16:22:42','Jordan Crook'),(5,1,'9ce338632181a06c8debd6de9658b74d','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545828','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Balderton Capital Invests In Web Backup Startup Archify','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/VeqCg0JRy-U/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/archify-logo.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"archify logo\" />One of the most frustrating online experiences for me is trying to track down a web page or tweet that I saw a few days ago. If I\'m lucky, I bookmarked the page or favorited the tweet, but most of the time I haven\'t, and so I can only sit there and fume.\n\nSo basically, a startup called <a href=\"http://www.archify.com\">Archify</a> is the answer to my prayers. It\'s a browser plugin that tracks every website you visit (excluding <a href=\"https\">[https]</a> pages and websites you visit in Incognito mode), and also allows you to connect your Facebook and Twitter accounts for archiving. Then, when you\'re trying to find something later, you just search the archives like you\'d search the Web.',1,'2012-05-03 15:56:45','Anthony Ha'),(6,1,'0e430c9f6136caebe4cb2ce5b573c64a','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545849','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Facebook Releases IPO Prospectus and Roadshow Video Featuring Interviews With Zuckerberg','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/XQE_65OuDwc/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/facebook-roadshow-video.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Facebook Roadshow Video\" />Watch Zuck, Sheryl Sandberg and the rest of the gang go to bat for Facebook in the <a href=\"http://facebook.retailroadshow.com/show/retail.html?m&#38;u=27962#\">promo video for its pre-IPO roadshow</a>. For your reading pleasure, I\'ve written a sportscaster-style play-by-play followed by some highlights. \n\nHit \"Read More\" to learn aboutÃ‚Â Facebook\'s mission, products and platform, advertising, finance, and future without having toÃ‚Â click past all the SEC disclaimers and sit through the 30-minute video.',1,'2012-05-03 15:56:22','Josh Constine'),(164,1,'9661ab0a2641f4413563b3a47357f644','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546390','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Gillmor Gang Live 05.04.12 (TCTV)','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/M5o5zZvEmbk/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2011/08/gillmore-gang-test-pattern.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Gillmor Gang test pattern\" />Gillmor Gang - Doc Searls, John Taschek, Kevin Marks, Robert Scoble, and Steve Gillmor. Live recording has concluded.',1,'2012-05-04 15:09:56','Steve Gillmor'),(7,1,'a3d84aeae9cb24386071f34cd6cbf4bc','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545729','2012-05-03 18:12:06','FacebookÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Ã¢â‚¬Å“OffersÃ¢â‚¬Â News Feed Coupons Launch In Self-Serve Beta For Local U.S. Businesses','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/dsGHFd6ocRw/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/102534329872055_1296335536.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"102534329872055_1296335536\" />Today any local U.S. business can <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/help/?faq=102534329872055#How-do-I-create-an-offer-for-my-Facebook-Page?\">start using Facebook\'s Offers product</a>Ã‚Â -- free-to-create coupons that businesses can share to the news feed, and that users can bring to brick-and-mortar stores for redemptions. First announced in February at the <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/03/04/facebook-marketing-conference/\">Facebook Marketing Conference</a>, the product has been in private testing with a select group of brands who worked with Facebook reps to run the offers. Now the promotional product is available in a self-serve interface.\n\nWhile it doesn\'t cost businesses anything to run offers, Facebook could still make money on them. If they perform well in the news feed and drive business to physical stores, those stores may spend more on Facebook ads that increase their Page fan counts -- and the subscriber bases for the coupons.',1,'2012-05-03 15:37:43','Josh Constine'),(8,1,'e5293c73cf1f84a894ba45832067a13c','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545490','2012-05-03 18:12:06','LinkedIn Beats The Street, Q1 Revenue Up 101 Percent To $188.5M; Net Income Up 140 Percent','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/pvStDDu3cxM/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/linkedin.png?w=100&amp;h=68&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"linkedin\" />Professional social network LinkedIn has just <a href=\"http://press.linkedin.com/node/1192\">released</a> Q1 earnings. Revenue for the first quarter was $188.5 million, an increase of 101% compared to $93.9 million in the first quarter of 2011. Net income for the first quarter was $5 million, compared to net income of $2.1 million for the first quarter 2011, in increase of 140%.  Non-GAAP EPS for the first quarter was $0.15. Analysts <a href=\"http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505244_162-57426764/ahead-of-the-bell-linkedin-to-report-1q-results/\">expected</a> earnings of $0.09 cents per share, with quarterly revenue in at $179 million. Clearly, the company blew past Wall Street expectations. \n\nÃ¢â‚¬Å“LinkedInÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s solid performance in the first quarter built on the companyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s momentum in 2011,Ã¢â‚¬Â said Jeff Weiner, CEO of LinkedIn. Ã¢â‚¬Å“We saw strength across all key metrics from member signups and engagement to significant revenue growth across our three product lines.Ã¢â‚¬Â',1,'2012-05-03 15:21:10','Leena Rao'),(9,1,'4974738c7defeaee3c5e92179c86e25f','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545771','2012-05-03 18:12:06','FacebookÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Early Shareholders Will Sell Up To $5.5 Billion With IPO. HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s WhoÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Selling What:','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/GWqLm6JaBNw/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/02/markzuckerberg.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"markzuckerberg\" />Facebook\'s early investors and employees may sell up to $5.5 billion alongside the company\'s offering. Facebook <a href=\"http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1326801/000119312512208192/d287954ds1a.htm\">said today that it is selling 180 million shares of stock at $28 to 35 a share</a>. On top of that, other stockholders are selling 157,415,352 shares. Those proceeds will <em>not </em>go to Facebook.\n\nChief executive Mark Zuckerberg is selling 30.2 million shares, or up to $1.05 billion, which will mostly go toward settling the multi-billion dollar tax bill he\'ll face when he exercises his options.\n\nZuck\'s not the only one selling shares though.Ã‚Â So are Accel\'s Jim Breyer*, Peter Thiel, LinkedIn founder Reid Hoffman and Zynga CEO Mark Pincus. Then there are the institutional entities like Accel* and DST. In fact, it\'s Breyer and his firm Accel that are walking away with the biggest immediate payday from the IPO. Who\'s <em>not</em> selling in this offering? Sean Parker, Facebook COO Sheryl Sandberg and Facebook co-founder Dustin Moskovitz.\n',1,'2012-05-03 15:16:34','Kim-Mai Cutler'),(10,1,'8148d1726e63e8c68597e7154004e9f3','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545790','2012-05-03 18:12:06','LinkedIn Acquires Professional Content Sharing Platform SlideShare For $119M','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/OYgfNIr2cko/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/upload-share-p.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"upload-share-p\" />LinkedIn has just <a href=\"http://press.linkedin.com/node/1191\">acquired</a> professional content sharing platform SlideShare for $119 million in cash and stock. We\'ve pasted the release below. \n\nSlideShare is a sharing platform for business documents, videos and presentations. SlideShare lets anyone share presentations and video and also serves as a social discovery platform for users to find relevant content and connect with other members who share similar interests. The company also has a huge enterprise following, and companies like IBM and others use the platform to curate content from all of their employees and partners on a branded page.\n',1,'2012-05-03 15:14:00','Leena Rao'),(11,1,'4ca0501d7570945c1c07ca217cf29d28','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545738','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Facebook S-1 Confirms IPO Share Price Of $28-$35, Raising $5B To $6.3B, Hardware Patent Lawsuit Threats','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/f0l9x67QnFU/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/facebook-s-1-to-ipo-seal.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Facebook S-1 To IPO Seal\" /><a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/tag/Facebook\">Facebook</a> just posted a <a href=\"http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1326801/000119312512208192/d287954ds1a.htm\">fith amendment to its IPO filing</a>, confirming the price range for its stock at IPO, how much it will raise, and noting the future threat of patent lawsuits from Yahoo over hardware in Facebook\'s <a href=\"http://opencompute.org/\">Open Compute Project</a>. The company is selling 180,000,000 shares of Class A common stock and is pricing them at $28-$35. That means they\'re raising between $5 Ã‚Â billion and $6.3 billion.Ã‚Â On top of that, existing shareholders are sellingÃ‚Â 157,415,352 shares.\n\nHere\'s the excerpt:\n<blockquote>Facebook, Inc. is offering 180,000,000 shares of its Class A common stock and the selling stockholders are offering 157,415,352 shares of Class A common stock. We will not receive any proceeds from the sale of shares by the selling stockholders. This is our initial public offering and no public market currently exists for our shares of Class A common stock. We anticipate that the initial public offering price will be between $28.00 and $35.00 per share.</blockquote>\nThis confirms the <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/05/03/facebook-ipo-less-than-100-billion/\">earlier pricing that we posted</a> about today. We had a more specific range than <em>The Wall Street Journal</em> or <em>The New York Times,</em> saying the price was at $27-$35. We were off by a dollar, but they said \'high 20s to mid 30s\' in their original stories.',1,'2012-05-03 14:35:13','John Biggs'),(12,1,'f600b6ffdebe314a57a63af4edde2653','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545525','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Elderly-Monitoring System BeClose Upgrades UI, Allows Caregivers To See The Big Picture','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/LBvJa4aWe00/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/ui.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"ui\" />BeClose is a small but interesting start-up in Tysons Corner, Virginia. They make home monitoring systems for the elderly, allowing them to stay at home even when they may be fragile or lack motility. The system consists of a number of motion sensors as well as a weight pad (to see when they\'re sleeping) and a panic button that notifies the authorities and kin if there\'s something wrong.\n\nThe new update to the UI creates a dashboard experience for caregivers. They can see, at a glance, sleep patterns, movement, and even weight. If something is amiss - like they\'re not getting out of bed after a certain time or whether they\'re leaving the house too little or too much - you can either call in to see what\'s up or go visit. Anyway, would it kill you to maybe go visit your mother? Hmm?',1,'2012-05-03 14:30:14','John Biggs'),(13,1,'72aac61645b460ce54b4064797ddb601','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545680','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Klout Releases New, Speedier API; Now Serves 1 Billion API Calls Per Day','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/WhdNAbP6oh0/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/klout.png?w=100&amp;h=52&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"klout\" /><a href=\"http://klout.com/\">Klout</a>, the startup that <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2009/11/17/klout-influence-twitter-list-authority/\">measures influence</a> on Twitter, Facebook, <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2011/06/14/klout-expands-influence-scoring-to-professional-social-network-linkedin/\">LinkedIn</a>, YouTube, <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2011/08/04/klout-adds-foursquare-but-how-much-will-it-boost-my-score/\">Foursquare</a>, <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2011/09/20/klout-now-measures-social-influence-on-google/\">Google+</a> and other social apps, has just <a href=\"http://corp.klout.com/blog/2012/05/more-ways-to-use-your-klout/\">released</a> a new version of its API and released a number of new stats about its API usage.\n\nKlout evaluates usersÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ behavior with complex ranking algorithms and semantic analysis of content to measure the influence of individuals on social networks. Klout says it now serves about one billion API calls per day, which is 80 times the amount of data we served this time last year. Klout says that in the last three months, API calls have risen from 10.5 billion to almost 30 billion per month. The company now has 6,000 API (up from 2,000 partners a year ago).',1,'2012-05-03 14:20:20','Leena Rao'),(14,1,'585283cdfe149549025ff3beb3d5dae7','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545620','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Samsung: The Death Of The Spec Gives Way To The Birth Of The Human Touch','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/fEfYhfpDbzs/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/galaxys3.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"galaxys3\" />If we have reached the Death of the Spec, then what Samsung wanted to introduce us to today was nothing short of the birth of the human touch. In the presentation launching the Galaxy S III, the first full half hour was very light on specs, with mention of only one -- the size of the screen (4.8\"-huge).\n\nInstead, what we got was long on references to intuitive design, with lots of non-tech buzzwords: \"nature,\" \"organic,\" and so on. The Galaxy S III is \"really designed for humans\" the company said today, again and again.\n',1,'2012-05-03 14:12:46','Ingrid Lunden'),(15,1,'693ed483c2ef0e1899be8c52b550ec28','http://techcrunch.com/?p=541214','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Ã¢â‚¬Å“In the Studio,Ã¢â‚¬Â Shasta VenturesÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ Rob Coneybeer Envisions An Internet Of Things','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/2sIgkofrzg0/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-01-at-12-18-57-pm.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen shot 2012-05-01 at 12.18.57 PM\" />\"In the Studio\" continues this week with a mechanical engineer who built and tested materials used in spacecraft, spent years on Sand Hill Road as a venture capitalist focused on semiconductors, software, and networking industries, and out of a desire to build something new in his career while in Silicon Valley, co-founded a new venture capital firm to invest in what he and his partners believe represents the next mass wave of innovation.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.shastaventures.com/team/rob_coneybeer\">Rob Coneybeer</a> isn\'t your run-of-the-mill venture capitalist. You wouldn\'t know it from first <a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/robconeybeer\">glance</a>, but Coneybeer has a deep technical and operating background, and spent time in industries which provided him a foundation to understand technology platforms across many different sectors over long periods of time. After spending nearly a decade as an investor, Coneybeer didn\'t want to spend his career in the Valley without getting into the game himself, and thus he and his partners co-founded <a href=\"http://www.shastaventures.com/\">Shasta Ventures</a>, a venture firm <a href=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/financial-organization/shasta-ventures\">focused</a> on software, mobile, and collaborative consumption and which has made stage-agnostic investments across an impressive array of companies in a short period of time.',1,'2012-05-03 14:00:20','Semil Shah'),(16,1,'b8e7dc595b906831c05335db7788e2c5','http://techcrunch.com/?p=539307','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Evive Launches With $2M From Angels To Help Cure Our Addiction To Bottled Water','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/LnuTPBOiUTY/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-02-at-2-24-24-am.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen shot 2012-05-02 at 2.24.24 AM\" />Let\'s be honest: Whether or not you\'ve recently hugged a tree, buying branded tap water in a plastic bottle for $1.50+ a pop seems ... well ... completely #$%^&#38;-ing ridiculous -- unless of course your village has yet to secure a reliable source of potable water. In that case, we understand. But, with colleges (and <a href=\"http://www.nacsonline.com/NACS/News/Daily/Pages/ND0430123.aspx\">apparently Concord, Massachusetts</a>) moving to or actually banning bottled water, a Pennsylvania-based startup, called <a href=\"https://www.evivestation.com/#splash\">Evive</a>, has developed an innovative, ergonomic solution for providing campuses (and beyond) with a better alternative.',1,'2012-05-03 13:57:43','Rip Empson'),(17,1,'fdd1d0e88b114bccfa173cf95052f4e2','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545639','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Yep, Revision3 Has Been Acquired By The Discovery Channel','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/OMGtY0IHa-o/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/revision3-logo.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"revision3 logo\" />The Discovery Channel is announcing that it has acquired online video company Revision3, <a href=\"http://allthingsd.com/20120503/discovery-channel-gets-a-web-video-arm-courtesy-of-revision-3/\">as reported in AllThingsD</a>.\n\nMy boss Eric Eldon <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/30/online-video-content-pioneer-revision3-in-acquisition-talks-with-the-discovery-channel/\">wrote on Monday night</a> that a deal was in the works, with a price between $30 million and $40 million. Looks like he was right: Discovery isn\'t releasing the terms, but AllThingsD is also hearing that the price was $30 million. Revision3 had raised $10 million from investors including Greylock Partners, Marc Andreessen, and Mark Cuban.',1,'2012-05-03 13:48:16','Anthony Ha'),(18,1,'8d2ea695e28bbd6892808b2b87aaaf51','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545645','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Due To Revenue Decline, Bankers Lower Facebook IPO Pricing To $27-35 Range','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/sDePaqA0IvA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/facebook-icon.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Facebook icon\" />We are hearing from bankers underwriting Facebook\'s initial public offering, that it will IPO at a $70 billion to $90 billion valuation, or $27-$35 a share. The reason for the valuation dropping below its speculated $100 billion mark is the sequential quarter-over-quarter revenue decline going into the first quarter revealed in itsÃ‚Â <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/23/facebooks-amended-s-1-500-million-mobile-users-paid-300m-cash-23-million-shares-for-instagram/\">recent S-1 amendment</a>. Ã‚Â While that\'s still going to be a landmark valuation for a consumer Internet company, but it could be a bit disappointing for some.\n\n\"If y/y rev growth had accelerated, we could be talking LinkedIn multiples. Plus LinkedIn has expanding margins, which Facebook doesn\'t,\" said a source. (Just for reference, LinkedIn trades at a price-earnings ratio of 913. If Facebook debuted at a $100 billion valuation, that would be 100X its trailing net income.)\n\nThe Wall Street Journal also reported that Facebook will debut at an $85 Billion to $95 Billion valuation, but we have our own independent sources who have confirmed this price range.\n',1,'2012-05-03 13:43:43','Josh Constine'),(19,1,'25cdfcf2ad8768a039596c7970a11bb3','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545614','2012-05-03 18:12:06','WePay Raises $10 Million To Scale Its Online Payment Platform','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/se17gIHJMpA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/wepay_logo.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"wepay_logo\" />Online payment platform <a href=\"http://wepay.com\">WePay</a> just announced that it has raised $10 million in a new financing round. This round was led by <a href=\"http://www.ignitionpartners.com/\">Ignition Partners</a>. Two of the company\'s existing investors, Highland Capital Partners and August Capital also participated in this round. WePay, which bills itself as the \"anti-PayPal,\" is a Y Combinator alumni and was founded in 2008. The company raised a total of $9.15 million in two previous rounds over the last two years. In today\'s announcement, WePay notes that this is a growth round and is meant to allow it to scale its technology and workforce.',1,'2012-05-03 13:43:28','Frederic Lardinois'),(20,1,'a090bdcaed4e9142c0d5152f378fe6e0','http://techcrunch.com/?p=545619','2012-05-03 18:12:06','Samsung Officially Reveals The Galaxy S III In London, Will Launch In U.S. This Summer','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/R57mhbjjdCA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/gs31.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"gs31\" />Samsung has just officially unveiled the long-awaited Galaxy S III at their event in London, and instead of boring you by telling you how momentous a moment this is for the company, I\'m just going to jump right into the nitty-gritty.\n\nThe Ice Cream Sandwich-powered Galaxy S III features a sizable 4.8-inch 720p HD Super AMOLED display along with a 1.9-megapixel front-facing camera mounted right above it. Inside its slim 8.6mm thick frame is the recently-revealed <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/25/confirmed-galaxy-s-iii-to-pack-samsungs-new-1-4ghz-exynos-4-quad-processor/\">1.4 GHz Exynos 4 Quad chipset</a>, 1GB of RAM, 16 or 32GB of storage, a 2100 mAh battery, and radios for Bluetooth 4.0, WiFi, and NFC connectivity. Around the back of the device is an 8-megapixel camera pod (sorry, no crazy Nokia-esque hijinks here). ',1,'2012-05-03 13:20:10','Chris Velazco'),(21,2,'c8053030501376d594f82c7bc6daf830','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/todays-scuttlebot-tom-waits-cat-and-facebook-stock-promotion/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Today\'s Scuttlebot:  Tom Waits Cat and Facebook Stock Promotion','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/todays-scuttlebot-tom-waits-cat-and-facebook-stock-promotion/','','The technology reporters and editors of The New York Times scour the Web for important and peculiar items. Thursday\'s selection includes Facebook\'s online promotional road show for its coming stock offering and a variation on the Nyan Cat video, featuring the musician Tom Waits.',1,'2012-05-03 17:32:53','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(22,2,'61cc0923db34f14b76d97bb71395a911','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/dealbook-loeb-accuses-yahoo-officials-of-resume-padding/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','DealBook: Loeb Accuses Yahoo Officials of RÃƒÂ©sumÃƒÂ© Padding','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/dealbook-loeb-accuses-yahoo-officials-of-resume-padding/','','In a letter to Yahoo\'s board, the activist investor Daniel S. Loeb said that Yahoo\'s chief executive and a board member listed college majors different from the ones they earned. <a href=\"http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/loeb-accuses-yahoo-officials-of-resume-padding/\">Read more &#187;</a>',1,'2012-05-03 15:09:14','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(23,2,'1a166b909774954cd3a34341f9d14c13','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/dealbook-facebook-to-set-i-p-o-price-range-after-market-close/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','DealBook: Facebook Sets Price Range at $28 to $35','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/dealbook-facebook-to-set-i-p-o-price-range-after-market-close/','','Facebook set the estimated price for its initial public offering at $28 to $35 a share on Thursday, a debut that could value the company at $86 billion. <a href=\"http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/facebook-to-set-target-after-market-close/\">Read more &#187;</a>',1,'2012-05-03 14:13:05','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(24,2,'c191a8a89fcfb86caff6baa7daebf199','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/selling-the-xbox-as-if-it-were-a-cell-phone/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Selling the Xbox as if It Were a Cellphone','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/selling-the-xbox-as-if-it-were-a-cell-phone/','','Microsoft has a plan to sell its Xbox game system more the way it would a cellphone, giving customers a break on the cost of the device as long as they commit to pay a monthly service bill. ',1,'2012-05-03 13:15:38','By NICK WINGFIELD'),(25,2,'537f6d4088cc02cace77504171f0f430','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/samsung-galaxy-s-iii/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Samsung Unveils New Version of Its Biggest Phone Hit','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/samsung-galaxy-s-iii/','','Samsung, the world\'s largest phone maker, released details of its latest smartphone, the Galaxy S III. Samsung\'s Galaxy S line of smartphones has been instrumental to its success in the smartphone market. ',1,'2012-05-03 13:01:34','By BRIAN X. CHEN'),(26,2,'f6c29e900f97c1860d38a279c2d1e31e','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/daily-report-europeans-rethink-their-google-inquiries/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Daily Report: Europeans Rethink Their Google Inquiries','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/daily-report-europeans-rethink-their-google-inquiries/','','European privacy regulators said Wednesday that they were considering reopening their inquiries into Google\'s collection of personal e-mails and Web searches for its Street View service, reports Kevin J. O\'Brien in Thursday\'s New York Times. The move came after revelations that collecting the Internet data had not been a lone programmer\'s error. ',1,'2012-05-03 06:57:36','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(27,2,'4696c8e6618d0d189430848c1dddb9fe','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/keeping-secrets-on-facebook/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Keeping Secrets on Facebook','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/keeping-secrets-on-facebook/','','About a fourth of Facebook users in the United States lie about themselves in order to protect their privacy, according to a new study in Consumer Reports. ',1,'2012-05-03 05:00:14','By SOMINI SENGUPTA'),(28,2,'b02bad44c10b94cf9724db62ce81e160','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/microsoft-taps-yahoo-scientists-for-new-york-research-lab/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Microsoft Taps Yahoo Scientists for New York Research Lab','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/microsoft-taps-yahoo-scientists-for-new-york-research-lab/','','Microsoft is setting up a research lab in New York, picking off a team of researchers from the struggling Yahoo. The initial group, Microsoft says, is just a start as it seeks to tap into the \"groundswell\" of science and technology development under way in New York. ',1,'2012-05-02 23:10:51','By STEVE LOHR'),(29,2,'2a742e513b7ce9413a6d19342c6d737f','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/todays-scuttlebot-open-data-and-turntable-fm/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Today\'s Scuttlebot: \'Open Data\' and Turntable.fm','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/todays-scuttlebot-open-data-and-turntable-fm/','','The technology reporters and editors of The New York Times scour the Web for important and peculiar items. Wednesday\'s selection includes how blind people are using iPhones and a discussion of how Zynga\'s purchase of Omgpop, the maker of the game Draw Something, is looking a month later.',1,'2012-05-02 17:53:55','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(30,2,'8c815428f64bc050bfffcc81e2d07361','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/state-of-mobile/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','The State of Mobile: Less Talking, Fewer Texts, More Data','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/state-of-mobile/','','People generally talk less on the phone and send fewer text messages now because there are so many ways to communicate over an Internet connection. Though this may seem obvious to anyone who owns a smartphone, a new study confirms the trend.',1,'2012-05-02 17:16:35','By BRIAN X. CHEN'),(31,2,'942237283b74bd8e32476407ecdb109e','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/video-complacency-at-google-and-facebook/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Video: Complacency at Google and Facebook','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/video-complacency-at-google-and-facebook/','','Nick Bilton and Quentin Hardy discuss how the success of companies like Google and Facebook makes it harder for them to understand what people are looking for in the next generation of products.',1,'2012-05-02 16:55:59','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(32,2,'78b9e47d869ace9b38fc9c07674fd611','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/video-r-i-m-rests-hopes-on-blackberry-10/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Video: R.I.M. Rests Hopes on BlackBerry 10','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/video-r-i-m-rests-hopes-on-blackberry-10/','','Brian X. Chen and Peter Lattman discuss Research in Motion\'s hopes for a comeback with BlackBerry 10. While people have been pessimistic about the company\'s chances to regain its footing in the smartphone market, the response to its new operating system was generally positive. ',1,'2012-05-02 16:46:57','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(33,2,'76de198ef3285f053bb742e6b4046d93','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/with-people-aplenty-twitter-turns-to-discovery/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','With People Aplenty, Twitter Aims to Cut Through the Noise','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/with-people-aplenty-twitter-turns-to-discovery/','','Twitter has updated the algorithm and design of its Discover feature to help users find things they will care about amid the flood of messages on the service. ',1,'2012-05-02 11:32:32','By NICK BILTON'),(34,2,'eff2c0e1a59b4de037d015cbc5799e40','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/facebooks-for-companies-beef-up/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','\'Facebooks\' for Companies Beef Up','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/facebooks-for-companies-beef-up/','','Jive Software, the leading maker of Facebook-type software for businesses, is releasing free and \"use anywhere\" versions which it hopes will encourage customers to use the cloud-based versions of its product, along with some powerful analytics. Like its competitors Yammer and Salesforce, Jive hopes it can make social communications the core of business.',1,'2012-05-02 07:00:40','By QUENTIN HARDY'),(35,2,'496e41d6ccfac571161b2190db2ada70','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/daily-report-new-york-city-sets-social-media-rules-for-teachers/','2012-05-03 18:12:34','Daily Report: New York City Sets Social Media Rules for Teachers','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/daily-report-new-york-city-sets-social-media-rules-for-teachers/','','New York\'s public-school teachers may not contact students through personal pages on Web sites like Facebook and Twitter, but can communicate through pages set up for classroom use, reports David W. Chen and Patrick McGeehan in Wednesday\'s New York Times, according to new rules by the city\'s Education Department.',1,'2012-05-02 06:56:01','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(36,3,'f8e4ab113fe01ab4cc3c36751f223a8d','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16670','2012-05-03 18:14:48','La Typographie moderne','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16670','','<p><a href=\"http://www.editions-b42.com/books/La-Typographie-moderne/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/B42-LaTypographieModerne.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.editions-b42.com/books/La-Typographie-moderne/\">La Typographie moderne</a></p>\n<p>SÃ¢â‚¬â„¢appuyant sur le postulat de JÃƒÂ¼rgen Habermas selon lequel la modernitÃƒÂ© est un Ã‚Â«projet inachevÃƒÂ©Ã‚Â», Robin Kinross situe les dÃƒÂ©buts dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢une vÃƒÂ©ritable pratique moderne de la typographie aux alentours de 1700, avec la publication, en Angleterre, du premier traitÃƒÂ© de typographie, les Mechanick exercises (1683-1684) de Joseph Moxon, et la crÃƒÂ©ation du romain du roi en France. Il livre ici une histoire de la typographie moderne envisagÃƒÂ©e dans un sens large, bien au-delÃƒÂ  du modernisme formel, en privilÃƒÂ©giant les dÃƒÂ©marches et les praticiens qui, en Europe ou aux Ãƒâ€°tats-Unis, ont su articuler savoir et pratique Ã¢â‚¬â€œ ÃƒÂ  lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢instar des rÃƒÂ©formateurs anglais ou des membres de la nouvelle typographie. En prenant en compte les avancÃƒÂ©es techniques et le contexte dans lequel les typographes opÃƒÂ¨rent, Robin Kinross met ainsi lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢accent sur les aspects sociaux, politiques, techniques et matÃƒÂ©riels qui informent leur pratique. LÃ¢â‚¬â„¢originalitÃƒÂ© de cet essai se situe ÃƒÂ  plusieurs niveaux : rÃƒÂ©cit vivant et critique des dÃƒÂ©veloppements de la typographie au cours des siÃƒÂ¨cles, il est enrichi par des exemples reprÃƒÂ©sentatifs, rarement montrÃƒÂ©s auparavant, et propose une ouverture pour dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢autres investigations.</p>\n<p>Les ÃƒÂ©ditions B42 poursuivent leur travail de traduction de textes majeurs de l&#8217;histoire du design et de la typographie et constituent ainsi un fonds critique indispensable. Cet ouvrage au point de vue inÃƒÂ©dit et jamais paru en franÃƒÂ§ais est une proposition nouvelle et extrÃƒÂªmement bien documentÃƒÂ©e sur lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢histoire de la typographie depuis le XVIIIe siÃƒÂ¨cle. Il vient combler un manque dans la thÃƒÂ©orie et lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢histoire de la typographie par lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ouverture et la prÃƒÂ©cision du point de vue critique de lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢auteur. </p>\n<p>ConfÃƒÂ©rences, avec Robin Kinross:<br />\n10 mai, 14h30, <a href=\"http://www.erba-valence.fr/actualites/esad-gv/actualites-2/\">Ãƒâ€°cole supÃƒÂ©rieure d&#8217;art et de design</a>, Valence<br />\n11 mai, 19h, <a href=\"http://www.centrepompidou.fr/Pompidou/Manifs.nsf/0/5CCD795707C1BD51C12579B300359262?OpenDocument&#38;sessionM=2.1.2&#38;L=1&#38;form=Actualite\">Centre Pompidou</a>, Paris</p>\n<p>Rencontre et signature, avec Robin Kinross:<br />\n12 mai, 18h30, <a href=\"http://yvon-lambert.com\">Librairie Yvon Lambert</a>, Paris</p>\n',1,'2012-05-03 10:47:43','manystuff'),(37,3,'891c304cc635c921b292d51694a27974','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16663','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Art=Life=Art. Dada>Fluxus','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16663','','<p><a href=\"http://www.museion.it/#897&#38;0&#38;en\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/04_Museion_Vaccari.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.museion.it/#897&#38;0&#38;en\">Art=Life=Art. Dada&gt;Fluxus</a> highlights the connections and elements of continuity between the Dadaism of the 1920s and the Fluxus movement which started in the 1960s. Presented on mobile shelving, the works invite interaction, encouraging visitors to study them close up and compose their own personal exhibition layout.</p>\n<p>Art as part of life (art=life), and not the opposite; breaking down barriers between what is deemed art and what is not, between playful and socially committed works of art. In 1916 Dadaism completely upended the prevailing concept of art, and the Fluxus movement of the early 60s drew on many elements and principles of Dada works.</p>\n<p>The exhibition opens with Marcel DuchampÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s famous Ã¢â‚¬Å“BoÃƒÂ®te-en-valiseÃ¢â‚¬Â. The installation, a limited edition production of the late 1930s which was reproduced by the artist himself in 1961, gathers around 60 miniature versions of his most important works, from his post-Futurist paintings to the legendary urinal. In the work Duchamp plays with the concepts of original and replica: the work is just one of the numerous ready mades and multiples in the show, typical manifestations of Dada and Fluxus. Both the ready mades Ã¢â‚¬â€œ appropriations of everyday items Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and the multiples, multiple editions of existing works, reject the idea of the work of art as a precious, unique one-off. The value of the work therefore lies not in the skill that went into producing it, but the artistÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s intellectual operation. And if the conceptual aspect prevails over the manual one, it follows that even a piece of cake or a biscuit can become part of a work of art.</p>\n<p>The exhibition features works by Erik Andersen, Joseph Beuys, George Brecht, John Cage/Calvin Sumsion, Christo, Giuseppe Chiari, Philip Corner, Marcel Duchamp, Ken Friedman, Raymond Hains, John Heartfield, Geoffrey Hendricks, Dick Higgins, Joe Jones, Charlotte Moorman, Nam June Paik, Ben Patterson, Lamberto Pignotti, Robert Rauschenberg, Pierre RÃƒÂ©stany, Mimmo Rotella, Sarenco, Daniel Spoerri, Ben Vautier, Jacques VilleglÃƒÂ©, Wolf Vostell and Bob Watts; and artistsÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ books by: Marcel Duchamp, Christo, Joseph Beuys, George Brecht, John Cage, Giuseppe Chiari, Philip Corner, Dick Higgins, Diter Roth, Daniel Spoerri, Klaus Staeck, Ben Vautier and Wolf Vostell. </p>\n<p>Until February 24, 2013<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.museion.it\">Museion</a>, Bolzano</p>\n',1,'2012-05-03 05:05:23','manystuff'),(38,3,'d20737cf95a0515ebb011d682dcc9b45','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16650','2012-05-03 18:14:48','ConfÃƒÂ©rence Pratique+Critique: Sara De Bondt & Antony Hudek','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16650','','<p><a href=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Cover-1-LR.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Cover-1-LR.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p>Pratique+Critique: Sara De Bondt &#38; Antony Hudek</p>\n<p>Founded in 2008 by <a href=\"http://www.saradebondt.com/\">Sara De Bondt</a> and Antony Hudek, <a href=\"http://occasionalpapers.org\">Occasional Papers</a> is a non-profit publisher of affordable books devoted to the histories of architecture, art, design, film and literature.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://occasionalpapers.org/?page_id=2007\">About Graphic Design</a> features a comprehensive selection of writings by renowned graphic designer, graphic design theorist and historian Richard Hollis, including interviews, essays, letters, articles, lectures and course outlines. About Graphic Design is densely illustrated with over 500 thumbnail images.</p>\n<p>ConfÃƒÂ©rence Pratique+Critique: <a href=\"http://occasionalpapers.org/\">Sara De Bondt &#38; Antony Hudek</a></p>\n<p>3 mai, 2012, 17h<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.ensad.fr/\">Ãƒâ€°cole Nationale SupÃƒÂ©rieure des Arts DÃƒÂ©coratifs</a>, Paris</p>\n',1,'2012-05-02 04:13:23','manystuff'),(39,3,'1507e5a7f4891ec3d3d78e72a7e0677e','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16630','2012-05-03 18:14:48','GRAPHIC #22 YALE','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16630','','<p><a href=\"http://graphicmag.kr/index.php?/issues/22-yale-/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/graphic22_yale_cover.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://graphicmag.kr/index.php?/issues/22-yale-/\">GRAPHIC #22 YALE </a></p>\n<p>Yale Special. Planned, edited &#38; designed by <a href=\"http://art.yale.edu/GraphicDesign\">graphic design department, Yale School of Art</a>.</p>\n<p>Participants and contributors: Ming Bai, Xavier Cerrilla, Matthew Chrislip, Inva Ãƒâ€¡ota, Kate Dewitt, Golnaz Esmaili, Harry Gassel, Njoki Gitahi, Janghyun Han, Suckzoo Han, Maxime Harvey, Kristian Henson, Tiff Hockin, Eric Hu, Azusa Kobayashi, Jen Lee, Weiyi Li, Andrew Lister, Yen-Wei Liu, Qiuye Liu, Rob Matthews, Nontsikelelo Mutiti, Cecilie Nellemann, Julia Novitch, Daniel Pizarro, Aurora Robles, Heesun Seo, Jaewon Seok, Jessica Svendsen, Chris Svensson, Stefan Thorsteinsson, Ghazaal Vojdani, Ryan Weafer, Jeseok Yi, Jack Balkin, James Berger, Julian Bittiner, Karla Britton, Craig Buckley, Francesco Casetti, Gregory Crewdson, Glen Cummings, Sheila Levrant De Bretteville, Keller Easterling, Paul Elliman, Michael Faison, Peter Halley, Roni Horn, Matthew Jacobson, Wayne Koestenbaum, Karel Martens, Dan Michaelson, Sigi Moeslinger, Alexander Nemerov, Margaret Olin, Sarah Oppenheimer, Mark Owens, Kevin Repp, Michael Rock, Elihu Rubin, Julika Rudelius, Holly Rushmaier, Susan Sellers, Rob Storr, Masamichi Udagawa, Daniel Van Der Velden, Linda Van Deursen, Lyneise Williams, Yale Gdmfa Ã¢â‚¬â„¢11, Timothy Young.</p>\n',1,'2012-05-01 06:21:19','manystuff'),(40,3,'8ec89e1baa81cff84240e0052f051554','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16573','2012-05-03 18:14:48','25th Brno Biennial  Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Talks','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16573','','<p><a href=\"http://www.moravska-galerie.cz/bienale-brno\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/25.BB_05.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.moravska-galerie.cz/bienale-brno\">25th Brno Biennial</a> consists of A an international competition, B an exhibition under a guest curator, C accompanying thematic shows and D an introductory three-day series of Biennial Talks.<br />\nThe core of the upcoming jubilee 25th Brno Biennial is its international competition, the aim of which is to present a broad spectrum of contemporary graphic design and its metamorphoses across media and forms. The related exhibition is based on works selected by a specialist board featuring designers and design theoreticians.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.moravska-galerie.cz/bienale-brno/sympozium/prednasky.aspx\">Lectures and presentations</a> by designers and design theoreticians: Andrew Blauvelt, Sulki &#38; Min, Zak Kyes, R. V. NovÃƒÂ¡k and Jan van Toorn, Na Kim, Kasia Korczak, AdÃƒÂ©la SvobodovÃƒÂ¡ &#38; Tereza HejmovÃƒÂ¡ &#38; Pauline Kerleroux, Karel Haloun, Jon Sueda, Experimental Jetset and Milan KnÃƒÂ­Ã…Â¾ÃƒÂ¡k, Karl Nawrot, James Langdon, Linked by Air, Christoph Keller and Katerina SedÃƒÂ¡.</p>\n<p>June 23-24, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.moravska-galerie.cz\">Moravian Gallery</a>, Brno</p>\n',1,'2012-04-27 02:32:10','manystuff'),(41,3,'34a6cbbfff09fe4ff621d64dcca7fd0d','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16569','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Moving Picture Show Ã¢â‚¬â€œ JÃƒÂ¼rg Lehni','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16569','','<p><a href=\"http://www.cig-chaumont.com/en/cig/page/international-poster-and-graphic-design-festival/exhibitions/moving-picture-show-jurg-lehni\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/b7d8c4794341ccf53a55fd080bfd39f9.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.cig-chaumont.com/en/cig/page/international-poster-and-graphic-design-festival/exhibitions/moving-picture-show-jurg-lehni\">Moving Picture Show</a><br />\nby <a href=\"http://lehni.org/\">JÃƒÂ¼rg Lehni</a></p>\n<p>The current migration from analogue to digital movie projections in cinemas across the globe is slowly rendering the medium of 35mm motion picture film obsolete, along with the technical equipment used to produce and screen such film.<br />\nIn Moving Picture Show, a scenario of production of animated drawings and text is created by reappropriating a process normally used by the film industry to etch subtitles into the emulsion layer of 35mm film using a high-powered precision laser. By etching away the emulsion, only the clear base of the film remains. Projected onto the screen, the lines appear bright and clear.<br />\nChanging the working range of the laser and replacing the software interface to such a machine leads to new possibilities: Animations and full-frame drawings can be realised on top of film. The film can either consist of existing material, film created purely for this purpose, or black, non-developed film.<br />\nDuring the 23rd International Poster and Graphic Design Festival in Chaumont, the jesuits chapel will be transformed into a workshop, a scenario of conception, production and projection of a series of short films produced in this way. Several contributing designers and artists are invited to engage with the production facility and collaborate on the contents of the show, producing films that will be projected repeatedly during the festival. Meanwhile the laser machine which is also present in the chapel is slowly producing new films for future screenings.<br />\nInvited Artists (not final): David Reinfurt, Karl Nawrot, Konstantin Grcic, Triin Tamm.</p>\n<p>May 26 &#8211; June 10, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.cig-chaumont.com/en/cig/page/international-poster-and-graphic-design-festival?archives=91\">International Poster and Graphic Design Festival</a>, Chaumont</p>\n',1,'2012-04-26 07:41:59','manystuff'),(42,3,'0d4c451b369d3b27b6190f67c153c6c5','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16561','2012-05-03 18:14:48','La Grande Ourse Ã¢â‚¬â€œ appel ÃƒÂ  candidatures','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16561','','<p><a href=\"http://www.parcsaintleger.fr/residences.php\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Capture-dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ÃƒÂ©cran-2012-04-26-ÃƒÂ -12.08.57.png\" /></a><a href=\"http://www.parcsaintleger.fr/residences.php\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Capture-dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ÃƒÂ©cran-2012-04-26-ÃƒÂ -12.08.57.png\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.parcsaintleger.fr/residences.php\">La Grande Ourse</a> est une rÃƒÂ©sidence de recherche, pensÃƒÂ©e et ÃƒÂ©laborÃƒÂ©e comme une master class proposÃƒÂ©e par les trois Ãƒâ€°coles Nationales SupÃƒÂ©rieures dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢Art, Bourges, Cergy, Dijon, le pÃƒÂ´le graphisme de Chaumont, et le Parc Saint LÃƒÂ©ger-Centre dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢art contemporain.<br />\nTrois artistes issus des ÃƒÂ©coles partenaires, un thÃƒÂ©oricien et un graphiste ÃƒÂ©mergents seront sÃƒÂ©lectionnÃƒÂ©s pour cette rÃƒÂ©sidence de recherche qui se dÃƒÂ©roulera durant trois mois, de janvier ÃƒÂ  mars 2013, sur le site du Parc Saint LÃƒÂ©ger, centre dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢art contemporain de Pougues-les-eaux.</p>\n<p>Par ce biais, La Grande Ourse souhaite renforcer lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢interaction entre recherche plastique, thÃƒÂ©orique et graphique. PensÃƒÂ©e sur un mode expÃƒÂ©rimental, son ambition est de crÃƒÂ©er les conditions de dÃƒÂ©veloppement dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢axes de recherches personnelles dans un environnement collaboratif. La rencontre dans un mÃƒÂªme espace-temps dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢une micro communautÃƒÂ© issue de trois disciplines distinctes de la crÃƒÂ©ation contemporaine poursuit une logique de dissipation des frontiÃƒÂ¨res propre au champ de lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢art afin de privilÃƒÂ©gier le partage de mÃƒÂ©thode, de recherche et de production.</p>\n<p>Au terme de cette pÃƒÂ©riode, un objet ÃƒÂ©ditorial, territoire commun aux rÃƒÂ©sidents, sera rÃƒÂ©alisÃƒÂ©. Cet objet collectif constituera un espace dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ÃƒÂ©change des positions artistiques de chacun, de convergence des rÃƒÂ©flexions conduites en commun, de questionnements et de dialogue de leur recherche et de leur pratique.	Quelle que soit sa forme, espace dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢exposition, journal de bord, album de famille, manuel dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢histoire, cet objet collectif sÃ¢â‚¬â„¢inscrira au croisement de la thÃƒÂ©orie et de la pratique, des arts visuels et des arts appliquÃƒÂ©s, de lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢art et de sa transmission.</p>\n',1,'2012-04-26 05:24:56','manystuff'),(43,3,'52e8027967b430a364263730a4c139bf','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16543','2012-05-03 18:14:48','STEINBERG, SAUL. THE NEW YORKER. NEW YORK, 1945Ã¢â‚¬â€œ2000. (HAROLD, WILLIAM, ROBERT, TINA, DAVID, EDS.)','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16543','','<p><a href=\"http://yucontemporary.org/saul-steinberg/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/saul-steinberg-and-inge-morath-07.jpg\" /></a><a href=\"http://yucontemporary.org/saul-steinberg/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/2_steinberg_s_0.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://yucontemporary.org/saul-steinberg/\">STEINBERG, SAUL. THE NEW YORKER. NEW YORK, 1945Ã¢â‚¬â€œ2000.<br />\n(HAROLD, WILLIAM, ROBERT, TINA, DAVID, EDS.)</a></p>\n<p>For more than fifty years, <a href=\"http://www.saulsteinbergfoundation.org/life_work.html\">Saul Steinberg</a> was The New YorkerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s in-house observer, visual epitome, and its chief cartoonist. This exhibition, naming The New YorkerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s consecutive editors, collects some two hundred of his one thousand published contributions, presented as is: magazines, collected through time, some slightly yellowed and hung with that irrevocable library smell&#8230;</p>\n<p>We canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t imagine how you could see SteinbergÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s stenographic line without seeing the page it is on. Ã¢â‚¬Å“Everything has a message,Ã¢â‚¬Â Steinberg noted. The circulatory system has a message, the page has a message, the ads have a message, the neighborhood of fiction and news have a message, all of it makes for juxtapositions as eerily apposite as anything the French surrealists or a blender could come up with. </p>\n<p>The exhibition program will include a lecture by the exhibition coordinators Robert Snowden and Scott Ponik, a talk by Stuart Bailey of Dexter Sinister on July 3, and a screening of The Right Way by Fischli and Weiss on Saturday, August 4.</p>\n<p>June 16 &#8211; August 10, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://yucontemporary.org/\">YALE UNION (YU)</a>, Portland</p>\n',1,'2012-04-25 23:58:34','manystuff'),(44,3,'f2f346f970dd9947469504f609987668','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16532','2012-05-03 18:14:48','ABOUT Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Independent Publishing Fair','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16532','','<p><a href=\"http://www.aboutabout.de/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/about_flyer_front_web_en.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p>&#8220;We are ABOUT to make history&#8221; is the motto of the first <a href=\"http://www.aboutabout.de/\">ABOUT Independent Publishing Fair</a> in Mainz. With more than 25 participants from all across the country and a focus on the presentation of studentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s publications from various art academies, it facilitates exchange and dialogue with like-minded people as well as the general public. </p>\n',1,'2012-04-25 00:40:17','manystuff'),(45,3,'a0a81324a3d8963bcbfb8993b97484d9','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16527','2012-05-03 18:14:48','PROJEKTIL 2012 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ WeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll be right there','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16527','','<p><a href=\"http://www.projektil.org/2012/beta/indexen.php\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/PROJEKTILwithouttext.jpeg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.projektil.org/2012/beta/indexen.php\">Projektil</a> is an international series of lectures at the Bauhaus-University in Weimar. It was initiated in 2007 by students of the Faculty of Art and Design due to a missing professorship in graphic design. Since then this event is presented annually and, because of the enormous success and request, its organization is passed on from students to students.<br />\nIn addition to presentations by leading personalities of the creative field, workshops of several daysÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ duration are offered to all students interested.<br />\nThis year, the guest speakers are invited to display their personal finding of paths and how barriers are faced in their daily work routine Ã¢â‚¬â€ along the lines of &#8220;WeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll be right there.&#8221;</p>\n<p>With Till Wiedeck&#38;Timm HÃƒÂ¤neke, Na Kim, Veronica Ditting, Manuel Raeder, Emil Kozak, Prof.Andreas Uebele, Patrick Desbrosses, JÃƒÂ¼rg Lehni, Schroeter&#38;Berger, Haw-linServices.</p>\n<p>Until July 21<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.uni-weimar.de\">BauhausÃ¢â‚¬â€œUniversity</a>, Weimar</p>\n',1,'2012-04-24 04:31:38','manystuff'),(46,3,'ba7d330891ee2ca328d1662bfc4f8f37','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16514','2012-05-03 18:14:48','BUNK: Celebrating 60 Years of the Independent Group','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16514','','<p><a href=\"http://www.ica.org.uk/32244/Talks/BUNK-Celebrating-60-Years-of-the-Independent-Group.html\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Celebrating-60-Years-of-the-Independent-Group.jpeg\" /></a> <a href=\"http://www.ica.org.uk/32244/Talks/BUNK-Celebrating-60-Years-of-the-Independent-Group.html\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/bunk2.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ica.org.uk/32244/Talks/BUNK-Celebrating-60-Years-of-the-Independent-Group.html\">BUNK: Celebrating 60 Years of the Independent Group</a></p>\n<p>&#8220;<a href=\"http://www.independentgroup.org.uk/\">The Independent Group</a> looked at, discussed, analysed, wrote about, designed, built and assembled a galaxy of highly significant work exploring contemporary culture Ã¢â‚¬Å“as foundÃ¢â‚¬Â. Using a range of sources including the pages of science-fiction magazines, Jackson PollockÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s paintings, Hollywood film, helicopter design, the streets of LondonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s East End and modernist architecture the Independent Group created a radical approach to looking at and working with visual culture.&#8221;</p>\n<p>ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s 60 years since the Independent Group first met, and the work is attracting increased attention on an international scale. This two day event celebrates the Independent GroupÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s legacy at the very institution which first fostered and encouraged it. Contributors explore the history and legacy of the Independent Group in relation to art, architecture, design, material culture, photography and critical theory.</p>\n<p>April 26-27, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.ica.org.uk\">Institute of Contemporary Arts</a>, London</p>\n',1,'2012-04-23 06:22:14','manystuff'),(47,3,'29f348d8a94930a1fe88ea910f9c8bf9','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16509','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Apartamento issue #09','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16509','','<p><a href=\"http://www.apartamentomagazine.com/issue.php?id=19\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/541339_10150725063778830_21599598829_9252269_988289570_n.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.apartamentomagazine.com\">Apartamento</a> is an everyday life interiors bi-annual magazine written in English. A place in print about people, not just objects.<br />\nApartamento features the homes and lives of creative people, both established and emerging, from all over the world. It understands interior design as a means of personal expression, showing how people arrange their homes and the solutions they find to the same problems that everyone has. Apartamento puts forward a fresh and simply crafted aesthetic. It cares about the way people live and their relationships to the places they live.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.apartamentomagazine.com/issue.php?id=19\">Apartamento issue #09</a> features Tierney Gearon, Duncan Fallowell, YrjÃƒÂ¶ Kukkapuro, Conor Donlon, Nanos Valaoritis,TomÃƒÂ¡s Nervi, Annabelle Dexter-Jones, Jean Abou, Li Edelkoort, Wolfgang Tillmans, Nic &#38; Jackie Harrison, Gonzalo MilÃƒÂ , Jordi Labanda, Jem Goulding, Ramdane Touhami, Chris Johanson &#38; Jo Jackson, BOPBAA, JosÃƒÂ© LeÃƒÂ³n Cerrillo, India Salvor Menuez, Nicolas CongÃƒÂ© &#38; Camille Berthomier, Henry Roy, Jeff Rian, Max Lamb, Reg Mombassa. Plus: a fiction supplement by Jocko Weyland and Amanda Maxwell.</p>\n',1,'2012-04-23 01:08:39','manystuff'),(48,3,'9c46aee56342b9286043482ec446f38d','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16497','2012-05-03 18:14:48','BradAndAngelina aka YGDMFA2012 aka Coachella aka GraphicMag22Release aka BookShelfBeta aka CharlesManson aka GRiSInternationalPerformance aka YaleGraphicDesignThesisShow12','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16497','','<p><a href=\"http://www.ygdmfa.com/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/AqNzUfdCAAAANo9.jpg-large.jpeg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ygdmfa.com/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/tumblr_m2atjeIOED1rq3nb1o1_1280.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ygdmfa.com/\">YaleGraphicDesignThesisShow12</a></p>\n<p>&#8220;KombuchaTea is a graphic design exhibition to be held at Green Hall Gallery in the Yale School of Art, opening May 5, 2012 at 6:00 PM. It is the work of 16 students, the launch of a magazine, an eBook platform, a Turbo Folk fanzine, and graphic design mixtapes. WrestleMania is 3 floors, 13 websites, 2 projections, 5 screens, 6 speakers, 232 printed pieces, and 2 sets of headphones (maybe).</p>\n<p>ChrisBrownAndRihanna maximizes all available resourcesÃ¢â‚¬â€using, subverting, interacting with, and exhausting all available networks and reconfiguring existing materials with a new agenda. You can call this hacking, you can call this Ã¢â‚¬Å“truth to materials,Ã¢â‚¬Â you can call this media agnosticism, or you can call this resourcefulness as we call for attention in crowded visual, audible and fourth-dimensional fields with fewer financial resources and an exponentially growing number of platforms for distribution. WheresMyRefund is a show without a hierarchy, in fact, its a show without a title. DumbAndDumber2 is a dynamic set of interactions which promotes both a disorienting sense of subversion and the utopian ideal of equivalence. CoryBooker is a trending search term, an aggregate as well as a calcified, specific time and place. This is RepublicanDebate aka Graphic22Release aka BookShelfBeta aka BalkaniaFanzineLaunch aka GRiSIntrnationalPerformance aka YaleGraphicDesignThesisShow2012.&#8221;</p>\n<p>April 26 &#8211; May 5, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://art.yale.edu/\">Yale School of Art</a>, New Haven</p>\n',1,'2012-04-21 17:43:49','manystuff'),(49,3,'1a310fdd1b10e38f18d68eae3fdaef4e','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16492','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Bauhaus: Art as Life','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16492','','<p><a href=\"http://www.barbican.org.uk/artgallery/event-detail.asp?ID=12409\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Bauhaus-Art-as-Life.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.barbican.org.uk/artgallery/event-detail.asp?ID=12409\">Bauhaus: Art as Life</a></p>\n<p>The biggest Bauhaus exhibition in the UK in over 40 years presents the modern worldÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s most famous art school. From expressionist beginnings to a pioneering model uniting art and technology, this London exhibition presents the BauhausÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ utopian vision to change society in the aftermath of the First World War. Bauhaus: Art as Life explores the diverse artistic production that made up its turbulent fourteen-year history and delves into the subjects at the heart of the school: art, culture, life, politics and society, and the changing technology of the age. </p>\n<p>Bauhaus: Art as Life will feature a rich array of painting, sculpture, design, architecture, film, photography, textiles, ceramics, theatre and installation. Exemplar works from such Bauhaus Masters as Josef and Anni Albers, Marianne Brandt, Marcel Breuer, Walter Gropius, Johannes Itten, Wassily Kandinsky, Paul Klee, Hannes Meyer, LÃƒÂ¡szlÃƒÂ³ Moholy-Nagy, Oskar Schlemmer, Ludwig Mies van der Rohe and Gunta StÃƒÂ¶lzl, will be presented alongside works by lesser-known Bauhaus artists and students. </p>\n<p>May 3 &#8211; August 12, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.barbican.org.uk\">Barbican</a>, London</p>\n',1,'2012-04-21 17:21:48','manystuff'),(50,3,'3d1946bed5e55dc356c3217ee4da96d3','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16452','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Jacqueline De JongÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Situationist Times, 1962-1967','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16452','','<p><a href=\"http://boo-hooray.com/the-situationist-times/de-jong-situationist-times/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/de-jong-photo-situationist-times_Email1.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://boo-hooray.com/the-situationist-times/de-jong-situationist-times/\">Jacqueline De Jong&#8217;s &#8211; Situationist Times, 1962-1967</a></p>\n<p>Dutch artist and graphic designer Jacqueline de Jong joined the Situationist International in 1960. De Jong suggested the publication of an English language newsletter in November of 1960, to be co-edited with British Situationist Alexander Trocchi (who was in prison at the time). The publication was widely discussed at Situationist conferences in 1961, and the first issue of The Situationist Times was published in May of 1962.<br />\nDe Jong was determined to produce &#8220;a completely free magazine, based on the most creative of the Situationist ideas.<br />\nThe archival materials, issues and artwork relating to the six issues of The Situationist Times, are a marriage of raging political polemic and superb and explosive visual art by masters such as De Jong, Jorn, Pierre Alechinsky, and Gruppe SPUR at the top of their game.</p>\n<p>May 9-25, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://boo-hooray.com\">Boo-Hooray</a>, New York</p>\n',1,'2012-04-19 13:58:01','manystuff'),(51,3,'d89d9e40ea99414b31a98013ca3ac738','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16442','2012-05-03 18:14:48','LE CATALOGUE ET SES HYBRIDES #2','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16442','','<p><a href=\"http://lecatalogueetseshybrides.tumblr.com/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/catalogue-moinsun-Noir-650.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://lecatalogueetseshybrides.tumblr.com/\">LE CATALOGUE ET SES HYBRIDES #2</a></p>\n<p>Le catalogue et ses hybrides met en scÃƒÂ¨ne des projets qui rendent compte de la diversitÃƒÂ© de lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢offre ÃƒÂ©ditoriale liÃƒÂ©e au contexte dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢exposition.<br />\nCes espaces imprimÃƒÂ©s de rencontres &#8211; format dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢interaction entre un lieu dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢art (centre dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢art, galerie, musÃƒÂ©e&#8230;), un commissaire, un artiste, un designer graphique Ã¢â‚¬Â¦ &#8211; questionnent notamment lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢objet livre comme alternative ÃƒÂ  lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢espace dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢exposition.<br />\nDe lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢objet documentaire &#8211; le catalogue &#8211; ÃƒÂ  la formule imprimÃƒÂ©e composite &#8211; livre dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢artiste &#8211; certaines de ces publications proposent un traitement plus complexe de la documentation des productions artistiques et des pratiques curatoriales.<br />\nSource, trace ou prolongement de lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ÃƒÂ©phÃƒÂ©mÃƒÂ¨re, chacune de ces expÃƒÂ©riences imprimÃƒÂ©es, rÃƒÂ©activÃƒÂ©es ÃƒÂ  chaque lecture, constitue un espace alternatif de mÃƒÂ©moire vive, un nouveau contexte dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢existence de lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢Ã…â€œuvre dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢art. EmancipÃƒÂ©, le catalogue dÃƒÂ©fie et contourne lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢exposition.<br />\nLe contexte dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢exposition gÃƒÂ©nÃƒÂ¨re des expÃƒÂ©rimentations ÃƒÂ©ditoriales mettant en tension lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢espace dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢exposition et la documentation traditionnelle. En voici un extrait:</p>\n<p>- une exposition de projets ÃƒÂ©ditoriaux contemporains <a href=\"http://lecatalogueetseshybrides.tumblr.com\">lecatalogueetseshybrides.tumblr.com</a><br />\n- un extrait de la collection <a href=\"http://www.collection-fmra.org/\">FMRA</a> du cneai=<br />\n- un libraire associÃƒÂ© <a href=\"http://theophilespapers.tumblr.com/\">ThÃƒÂ©ophileÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Papers</a></p>\n<p>Samedi 28 avril<br />\n17h, <a href=\"http://www.museumofmuseum.com/\">Museum of Museum</a>: confÃƒÂ©rence-performance<br />\n18h, <a href=\"http://www.jslb.fr/\">JÃƒÂ©rÃƒÂ´me Saint-Loubert BiÃƒÂ©</a> &#38; <a href=\"http://www.rearsound.net/\">Yann SÃƒÂ©randour</a>: Discussion</p>\n<p>27-29 avril 2012<br />\nvernissage vendredi 27, 18h-21h<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.moinsun.com/\">Le Moinsun</a>, Paris</p>\n',1,'2012-04-17 07:55:30','manystuff'),(52,3,'8538b6fdecf327a1af18417d887afe99','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16436','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Hey Now!','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16436','','<p><a href=\"http://colophon.info/&#38;.htm\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Hey-Now-Book-launch.png\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://colophon.info/&#38;.htm\">Hey Now!</a><br />\nby <a href=\"http://www.ourpolitesociety.net/\">Jens Schildt</a></p>\n<p>Walking along, but more importantly, looking down while walking along. The ground that you see when you are on your way &#8211; home (from a night out), or the other way &#8211; to work perhaps? You might be interested in letters, the things that usually [seem to] go back on themselves. You are always looking for things that remind you of them, things that change your conception of them Ã¢â‚¬â€œ things that will lead to new designs, new formal solutions, or simply comforts making you feel less bad about yourself. Sometimes these things are best found by chance, or better, by detritus. Detritus with limits. These things you might want to collect, carry around with you; in your phone&#8217;s memory.</p>\n<p>Hey Now!, assembled by Jens Schildt and designed together with <a href=\"http://colophon.info/\">David Bennewith</a>, is the second booklet in a series of publications dedicated to the typographical <a href=\"http://colophon.info/&#38;.htm\">And</a>. Published by Silver Fern Press/Colophon.</p>\n<p>Book launch April 19, 7pm<br />\n<a href=\"http://lostproperty.cx/\">Lost Property</a>, Amsterdam</p>\n',1,'2012-04-16 10:52:56','manystuff'),(53,3,'b1e485c994ca382f3a6862cf70a614b8','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16431','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Pour une critique du design graphique Ã¢â‚¬â€œ PrÃƒÂ©sentation','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16431','','<p><a href=\"http://www.editions-b42.com/books/pour_une_critique_du_design_graphique/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/552315_366671913374560_152586198116467_1027113_1311289122_n.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.editions-b42.com/books/pour_une_critique_du_design_graphique/\">Pour une critique du design graphique</a><br />\nDix-huit essais, Catherine de Smet</p>\n<p>Comment le logo du Centre Pompidou a-t-il ÃƒÂ©tÃƒÂ© crÃƒÂ©ÃƒÂ©? Une thÃƒÂ©orie urbaine peut-elle sÃ¢â‚¬â„¢exprimer dans la conception matÃƒÂ©rielle dÃ¢â‚¬â„¢un livre? Le design graphique a-t-il servi la cause des femmes? En quoi consistent les archives spÃƒÂ©cialisÃƒÂ©es?<br />\nCet ouvrage est le premier recueil de textes de lÃ¢â‚¬Ëœhistorienne de lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢art et critique Catherine de Smet.</p>\n<p>25 avril, 18h30<br />\n<a href=\"http://lemontenlair.free.fr/\">Librairie Le Monte en lÃ¢â‚¬â„¢air</a>, Paris  </p>\n',1,'2012-04-16 01:50:24','manystuff'),(54,3,'4528634a06d3b981b49e4b73e5df926a','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16424','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Things to Do','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16424','','<p><a href=\"http://www.museum-gestaltung.ch/en/exhibitions/exhibitions-2012/100-years-of-swiss-graphic-design/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Karte.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.museum-gestaltung.ch/en/exhibitions/exhibitions-2012/100-years-of-swiss-graphic-design/\">Things to Do</a><br />\ncompiled by <a href=\"http://www.blokes.ch/\">Rafael Koch</a>, <a href=\"http://lehni.org/\">JÃƒÂ¼rg Lehni</a> and <a href=\"http://lehni-trueb.ch/\">Urs Lehni</a></p>\n<p>The world of instruments available to the designer has expanded dramatically in recent years and thanks to rapid technological progress is today available to a broad mass of users. The works shown here reflect this democratization of the means used in various ways. On the one hand new production processes created especially for specific situations are employed, while on the other hand existing processes are appropriated, adapted and transformed. This produces an distinct aesthetic, while at the same time questioning the role of technology and its standards. The works in Ã¢â‚¬Å“Things to DoÃ¢â‚¬Â operate within a deliberately restricted range of design possibilities. These stubborn tools can do almost nothing, but they can do it all the better.</p>\n<p>With Hisham Almannai, JÃƒÂ¼rg Lehni &#38; <a href=\"http://field-trip.org/\">Alex Rich</a>, <a href=\"http://www.maximage.biz/\">Maximage</a>, <a href=\"http://www.voidwreck.com/\">Karl Nawrot</a>, <a href=\"http://jonathanpuckey.com/\">Jonathan Puckey</a>, <a href=\"http://www.rokfor.ch/\">Rokfor</a>, <a href=\"http://rollo-press.com/\">Rollo Press</a>, <a href=\"http://www.ecal.ch/\">ÃƒÂ©cal Lausanne</a>.</p>\n<p>During <a href=\"http://www.manystuff.org/?p=15329\">100 Years of Swiss Graphic Design</a><br />\nApril 19 &#8211; June 3, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.museum-gestaltung.ch\">Museum fÃƒÂ¼r Gestaltung</a>, ZÃƒÂ¼rich</p>\n',1,'2012-04-13 03:59:52','manystuff'),(55,3,'615ed929a30d9aa79f2af77a8257f668','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16404','2012-05-03 18:14:48','Ecstatic Alphabets/Heaps of Language','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16404','','<p><a href=\"http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/exhibitions/1231\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/moma_ecstaticalphabets_auerbach_howtospellthealphabet.jpg\" /></a><a href=\"http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/exhibitions/1231\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/moma_ecstaticalphabets_ebner_rawwar.jpg\" /></a><br />\n<a href=\"http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/exhibitions/1231\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/moma_ecstaticalphabets_historical_nauman_rawwar_bma.jpg\" /></a><a href=\"http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/exhibitions/1231\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/moma_ecstaticalphabets2012_experimentaljetset_zangtumtum.jpg\" /></a><br />\n<em>Tauba Auerbach. How to Spell the Alphabet. 2005 &#8211; Shannon Ebner. RAW WAR. 2004 &#8211; Bruce Nauman. Raw War. 1970 &#8211; Experimental Jetset. Zang Tum Tum. If You Want It. 2003 </em><br />\n<br /> </br><br />\n<a href=\"http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/exhibitions/1231\">Ecstatic Alphabets/Heaps of Language</a> explores the material qualities of language in contemporary art across a wide range of mediums. The exhibition looks at some of the ways contemporary artists have experimented with language, freeing it from the page and from its communicative and descriptive duties.</p>\n<p>The contemporary works featured in this exhibition belong to a distinguished history of<br />\npoem/objects and concrete language experiments dating to the beginnings of modernism, and<br />\ninclude both Futurist and Dada objects as well as Neo-Dada experiments of the late 1950s, and works that sprang from international literary movements like concrete and sound poetry in Europe, Latin America, and the United States. This history is presented in the form of a timeline of objects in many mediums that tell a story of concrete language in visual art.<br />\nArtists in this historical section of the exhibition include: Carl Andre, Marcel Broodthaers, Henri Chopin, Marcel Duchamp, Ian Hamilton Finlay, John Giorno, Kitasono Katue, Ferdinand Kriwet, Liliane Lijn, Filippo Tommaso Marinetti, Bruce Nauman, Lawrence Weiner, and others.<br />\nArtists in the contemporary section of the exhibition include: Ei Arakawa/Nikolas Gambaroff, Tauba Auerbach, Dexter Sinister (David Reinfurt and Stuart Bailey), Trisha Donnelly, Shannon Ebner, Paul Elliman, Experimental Jetset, Sharon Hayes, Karl Holmqvist, Paulina Olowska, Adam Pendleton, and Nora Schultz. </p>\n<p>Although they are similar in inspiration, the contemporary works in Ecstatic Alphabets/Heaps of Language represent a radical updating of the concrete language experiments of the 20th century. Moving freely among disciplines, the contemporary artists in this exhibition function simultaneously as poets, writers, performers, and graphic designers, producing hybrid works of art in which the letter, the word, and the phrase are transcribed into sounds, symbols, pictures, or patterns, scrambled, negated, and most importantly, freed from the page and, in some cases, the duties of communication altogether.</p>\n<p>Ecstatic Alphabets/Heaps of Language is accompanied by a publication designed and produced by Dexter Sinister that includes text by Ms. Hoptman, reproductions of works in the exhibition, and an exhibition checklist. The publication also exists as an issue of the composite printed and electronic publication Bulletins of the Serving Library, a continuing series published twice-yearly by Dexter Sinister.</p>\n<p>May 6Ã¢â‚¬â€œAugust 27, 2012<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.moma.org\">MoMA</a>, New York</p>\n<p> </br></p>\n',1,'2012-04-11 02:24:39','manystuff'),(56,4,'e1af7f8cae04e10c9f8f31760e111cc4','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24476','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Latest Ã¢â‚¬Å“drawingÃ¢â‚¬Â experiments by Kynd  / openFrameworks','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/3QHVXmo4qmM/','','<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/kynd_drawing01.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/kynd_drawing01-640x360.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p>Latest set of &#8220;drawing&#8221; experiments by Kynd continue to impress. We already wrote about Kynd&#8217;s work some months ago where he used openFrameworks to create <a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/openframeworks/pencil-drawing-openframeworks/\">pencil-like drawings of photographs</a>. This new set, once again using <a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/category/openframeworks/\">openFrameworks</a> includes sand drawings, pink bacteria dance and aÃ‚Â quick study on watercolor-like texture. Whereas <a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/index.php?s=realism\">realism</a>/replica may be the starting point for many ofÃ‚Â Kynd&#8217;s pieces, IÃ‚Â particularlyÃ‚Â enjoy when they begin to develop a life of their own &#8211; especially the case of pink bacteria (reactionÃ¢â‚¬â€œdiffusion<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reaction%E2%80%93diffusion_system\">?</a>)Ã‚Â and sand.Ã‚Â  See videos below<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/openframeworks/latest-drawing-experiments-by-kynd-openframeworks/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_campaign=rss-mo-more&amp;utm_medium=rss\">Continue reading.... Latest &#8220;drawing&#8221; experiments by Kynd  / openFrameworks</a></p>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=3QHVXmo4qmM:IunOsQdfMcE:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/3QHVXmo4qmM\" />',1,'2012-05-03 15:16:29','Filip'),(57,4,'be0b5df68743daafd8bf5b967f4a4fb0','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24472','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Flash Developer/Creative Technologist at Kitcatt Nohr Digitas','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/5pST1F7kdP4/','','<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/20120503-093456.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/20120503-093456.jpg\" alt=\"20120503-093456.jpg\" /></a></p>\nCompany: <a href=\"http://kitcattnohrdigitas.com/\">Kitcatt Nohr Digitas</a>\n<p>Location: London, UK<br />\nType: Technologist<br />\nJob Type: Full-Time</p>\nDescription\n<p>The Agency<br />\nKitcatt Nohr Digitas is one of the UKÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s leading digital agencies. We boast an enviable client list covering virtually every sector: John Lewis, Waitrose, Puma, Lexus, Toyota, Proctor &amp; Gamble, Coca-Cola, Starbucks, Aviva Investors, Asus, Delta Airlines, Visit Wales and RNIB. We pride ourselves on being creatively strong, strategically sharp and technologically adept.<br />\nKitcatt Nohr Alexander Shaw was born in 2002. It went on to win a raft of awards; including four Agency of the Year awards, 85 creative and effectiveness awards as well as being named one of the Sunday TimesÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ Best Small Companies to Work For 2010. In March 2011 it merged with Digitas London, part of the worldÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s largest digital network and itself a multi award winner to form Kitcatt Nohr Digitas. The new agency has already delivered great things.</p>\n<p>The Culture<br />\nWe take it as read that most candidates can Ã¢â‚¬Ëœdo the jobÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ but for us thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not enough. Cultural fit is critical.<br />\nOur culture is driven by our belief in creative intelligence &#8211; a creed that demands constant questioning. For us the best work has yet to be done. WeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re immensely proud of the culture weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve created that fosters this approach. Open, honest and challenging Ã¢â‚¬â€œ we value intelligent opinions not egos.</p>\n<p>The Role<br />\nWeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re looking for someone with solid programming skills in AS3, who can handle pretty much any challenge. The main part of the role is building elegant, scalable Flash applications, scoping and architecting projects, contributing to concepting and building rapid prototypes. ThatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not to say that you wonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be occasionally asked to fix a banner, but at least it will be a break from concentrating on the complex architecture of your latest application.</p>\n<p>As you will know, the role of a Flash developer is quickly diversifying and we our reshaping our Flash team to match. The majority of the work we do in the Flash team is currently Flash, but we are training and exploring; iOS, Andrioid, HTML5, Processing, Open Frameworks, interactive installations etc. Some current labs projects include a wall-size interactive LED installation controlled by Kinect and the web, NFC reading apps to work with Nexus phones and Augmented Reality native iOS apps.</p>\n<p>Requirements<br />\nStandard Skills<br />\n-Robotlegs &amp; PureMVC<br />\n-Eclipse-based IDE<br />\n-Consistent and extendable coding style<br />\n-Solid knowledge of design patterns<br />\n-Can pick up new technologies/APIs quickly<br />\n-Passionate about technology<br />\n-Version control<br />\n-Excellent time management<br />\n-Excellent communication skills</p>\n<p>Additional Beneficial Skills<br />\n-Mobile<br />\n-Javascript<br />\n-Other programming languages</p>\n<p>Overall<br />\n-Great attitude, self-sufficient when required<br />\n-Loves learning fast!</p>\n<p>Let us know if you&#8217;re interested by sending us an email (careers_uk@digitas.com) including work history, a resume and some links to your best work.</p>\n\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=5pST1F7kdP4:W215STGsAsE:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/5pST1F7kdP4\" />',1,'2012-05-03 03:35:46','Jobs'),(58,4,'087351a0628eb176218f69fb0f379254','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24452','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Ã¢â‚¬ËœFeel MeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ by Marco Triverio Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Digital touch and new channels for bit-intimacy','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/_sIxc0UAMpQ/','','<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/feelme10.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/feelme10-640x398.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p>Feel Me is a project byÃ‚Â Marco TriverioÃ‚Â that explores the gap between synchronous and asynchronous communication using our mobile device in attempt to &#8220;connect differently&#8221; and enrich digital communications. Whereas we draw lines between phone conversations and sms messages, Feel Me looks for space in between that would allow you to be intimate in realtime,Ã‚Â non-verbally using touch<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/iphone/feel-me-by-marco-triverio-digital-touch-and-new-interactive-channels-for-bit-intimacy/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_campaign=rss-mo-more&amp;utm_medium=rss\">Continue reading.... &#8216;Feel Me&#8217; by Marco Triverio &#8211; Digital touch and new channels for bit-intimacy</a></p>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=_sIxc0UAMpQ:X1nB1R3C5Kk:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/_sIxc0UAMpQ\" />',1,'2012-05-02 09:23:26','Filip'),(59,4,'637c1b90862effae5d064ce23a52fe27','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24444','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Technical Lead Ã¢â‚¬â€œ UX Lab at INSTRUMENT','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/LKiO53A__-c/','','<img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creative_applications_badge_instrument.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\nCompany:Ã‚Â <a href=\"http://www.weareinstrument.com/\">INSTRUMENT</a>\n<p>Location:Ã‚Â Portland, Oregon, USA<br />\nType:Ã‚Â Technologist<br />\nJob Type:Ã‚Â Full-Time</p>\nDescription\n<p>The Instrument UX Lab is looking for a seasoned creative developer with a rare passion for making the impossible seem easy. As the Technical Lead at Instrument Labs, youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll be working with the UX Design Director to develop an open Lab environment where innovation happens naturally and with a purpose.</p>\n<p>We want you to consider Instrument Labs your personal R&amp;D space for creating and developing projects that are both experimental and client specific. For you, Ã¢â‚¬ËœdifficultÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ is a fun problem to solve. From building large, multi-screen installations to browser based interactives, or the next generation mobile apps, they are all just different means of turning an idea into something jaw dropping. Experimental to the core, you have solid programming experience making complex designs and fluid interactivity come to life on a variety of platforms such as OpenFrameworks, OpenGL, Processing &amp; Cinder. And it goes without saying that you understand the interplay of hardware infrastructure and the custom software necessary to make an experience come to life.</p>\n<p>You\\&#8217;ll be teaming up with us to develop concepts that use both old school, new and yet to be conceived technology. The following is a list of technologies that we are looking to explore:</p>\n<p>* Large-format, multi-screen, 60fps Interfaces<br />\n* Gestural sensing in 3D (Computer vision, Kinect etc.)<br />\n* New and evolving UI paradigms such as eye tracking, gesture &amp; touch<br />\n* Display/Projector seaming<br />\n* Projection mapping<br />\n* Physics simulations<br />\n* Motion Tracking<br />\n* LED installations</p>\n<p>You have 6-10 years experience with interface development using some the following:</p>\n<p>* OpenGL<br />\n* C++<br />\n* Open Frameworks<br />\n* Processing<br />\n* Cinder<br />\n* AS3<br />\n* C++<br />\n* Cinder<br />\n* Canvas<br />\n* Html5<br />\n* Javascript<br />\n* Ios &#8211; cocoa, objective c<br />\n* Flash (sterling etc.)<br />\n* Vvvv<br />\n* Max msp</p>\n<p>Additional Expectations:</p>\n<p>* Work with a sense of urgency (without panic) to deliver consistently<br />\n* Approach your work with an open, flexible outlook and a focus on innovation<br />\n* Engage with a positive attitude within the larger team to produce the best possible product and results<br />\n* Maximize your time and output by thinking creatively and working smarter, not just harder</p>\n<p>What We Offer</p>\n<p>* Competitive salary, full benefits package including medical, dental, vision coverage and 401k<br />\n* A great new work space in NE Portland, Oregon<br />\n* A collaborative, progressive, team development environment<br />\n* Access to innovative, creative projects with clients like Nike, Google. Microsoft and Intel<br />\n* Paid holidays and vacation/ personal time<br />\n* A team of people that work smart and play hard<br />\n* Opportunities to make a difference in a small, highly productive environment</p>\n<p>Let us know if you&#8217;re interested by sending us an email (jobs@weareinstrument.com) including work history, a resume and some links to your best work.</p>\n<p>NO RECRUITERS PLEASE</p>\n\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=LKiO53A__-c:2u1flP0tf14:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/LKiO53A__-c\" />',1,'2012-04-30 14:17:02','Jobs'),(60,4,'54fa0f9582eb2eb713a6424a8485d760','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24423','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Ã¢â‚¬ËœAffection StationÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ by Salvador Orara Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Reconnecting to our devices..','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/2t9H66HK7xY/','','<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/station_01_wind_tunnel.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/station_01_wind_tunnel-640x426.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p>(ARL) Affection Research Lab: Affection Stations is aÃ‚Â thesis project by Salvador OraraÃ‚Â searching for ways to reconnect to our devices to facilitate revelations.Ã‚Â They are designed as immersive installations which listen, and transcode a device&#8217;s unique incidental sound, exposing them to be more than just tools, toys, or gizmos but content generators revealing our intimate relation to them<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/processing/affection-station-by-salvador-orara-reconnecting-to-our-devices/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_campaign=rss-mo-more&amp;utm_medium=rss\">Continue reading.... &#8216;Affection Station&#8217; by Salvador Orara &#8211; Reconnecting to our devices..</a></p>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=2t9H66HK7xY:mXp2UnjoNts:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/2t9H66HK7xY\" />',1,'2012-04-30 05:45:42','Filip'),(61,4,'39f3ecb18b4e0aaa2c532c70eeaabb75','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24293','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Tripwire by J.M. Albert and A. Fure Ã¢â‚¬â€œ A wall of strings in constant flux','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/dLlIddaRTIw/','','<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/maxmsp/tripwire-by-j-m-albert-and-a-fure-a-wall-of-strings-in-constant-flux/attachment/tripwire_104_2_1000x707/\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/tripwire_104_2_1000x707-640x452.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p><em>Tripwire</em> (2011) is a kinetic installation by the French visual artist Jean-Michel Albert and American composer Ashley Fure. A vertical set of 18 (or 24) elastic strings Ã¢â‚¬â€œ each individually motorized and controlled via MaxMSP/Jitter Ã¢â‚¬â€œ is set into an undulating motion, creating a wall of geometrical apparitions in constant flux.<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/maxmsp/tripwire-by-j-m-albert-and-a-fure-a-wall-of-strings-in-constant-flux/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_campaign=rss-mo-more&amp;utm_medium=rss\">Continue reading.... Tripwire by J.M. Albert and A. Fure Ã¢â‚¬â€œ A wall of strings in constant flux</a></p>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=dLlIddaRTIw:6y6m5AQ4F64:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/dLlIddaRTIw\" />',1,'2012-04-29 16:22:06','Alexander Scholz'),(62,4,'1590af3dc4968135c8380db61b4a59fe','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24347','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Konfetti for iPad Ã¢â‚¬â€œ  Playful mirror image using OpenSceneGraph Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Stephan Huber','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/6z5M1cl6O5A/','','\n<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/konfetti01.png\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/konfetti01-640x257.png\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p>Latest piece by Stephan Maximilian HuberÃ‚Â usingÃ‚Â OpenSceneGraph andÃ‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å“cefixÃ¢â‚¬Â comes in the shape of iPad app called Konfetti. A fun little experimentÃ‚Â that uses the image captured by the camera andÃ‚Â dissolvesÃ‚Â it into a number of dots that follow the movements in front of the camera, and invite you to play with your mirrorÃ‚Â image.Ã‚Â Additionally, you can intervene the flow of theÃ‚Â dotsÃ‚Â by touching the screen<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/ipad/konfetti-for-ipad-playful-mirror-image-using-openscenegraph-stephan-huber/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_campaign=rss-mo-more&amp;utm_medium=rss\">Continue reading.... Konfetti for iPad &#8211;  Playful mirror image using OpenSceneGraph &#8211; Stephan Huber</a></p>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=6z5M1cl6O5A:WmLGUQ6W_bM:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/6z5M1cl6O5A\" />',1,'2012-04-27 11:56:58','Filip'),(63,4,'e342b74d4fab046ab45d613795ee7583','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24328','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Interactivos?Ã¢â‚¬â„¢12 Dublin: Hack the City (Call for Proposals)','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/yuNO6fP_V1c/','','<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/interactivos.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/interactivos-640x480.jpg\" alt=\"Interactivos?09 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Garage Science\" /></a></p>\n<p>Interactivos?09 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Garage Science, photo: Alejandro Tamayo</p>\n<p>A call for proposals for the upcomingÃ‚Â instalmentÃ‚Â of Medialab-Prado&#8217;s excellentÃ‚Â Interactivos? research platform has been posted and it looks quite promising.Ã‚Â &#8221;Interactivos?&#8217;12 Dublin: Hack the City. Current and Future Needs&#8221; is being produced in collaboration with Science Gallery to facilitate the production of projects that engage urban infrastructure and discourse.<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/news/interactivos12-dublin-hack-the-city-cfp/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_campaign=rss-mo-more&amp;utm_medium=rss\">Continue reading.... Interactivos?&#8217;12 Dublin: Hack the City (Call for Proposals)</a></p>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=yuNO6fP_V1c:2V-JtCKnlIQ:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/yuNO6fP_V1c\" />',1,'2012-04-27 09:33:15','Greg J. Smith'),(64,4,'df5d1d709133724e269fa3ceab3d56a2','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24321','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Experienced OpenGL Programmer Wanted at Resolume HQ','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/vAY-bvyRKfg/','','<img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Resolume.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\nCompany:Ã‚Â <a href=\"http://www.resolume.com/\">Resolume VJ Software</a>\n<p>Location:Ã‚Â Den Haag,Ã‚Â Netherlands<br />\nType:Ã‚Â Creative Code<br />\nJob Type:Ã‚Â Full-Time</p>\nDescription\n<p>Our company is growing so we so we are in need of some extra hands &amp; brains to help us shape the future of live visuals. If you\\&#8217;re an experienced C/C++ OpenGL developer then get in touch, we have a full-time position available here in The Hague.</p>\n<p>At Resolume we create one of the most popular VJ tools on the market.<br />\nCheck out our website to get a feel of what we are all about.<br /> <a href=\"http://resolume.com/\">[resolume.com]</a> </p>\n<p>Or watch the video of our latest release to see what you could be working on in the near future:<br /> <a href=\"http://resolume.com/software/\">[resolume.com]</a> </p>\n<p>Qualifications<br />\n* 5+ years experience in developing software using C/C++ &amp; OpenGL on Mac OS X &amp; Windows<br />\n* Fluent with GLSL shading language<br />\n* Advanced foosball skillz</p>\n<p>Plusses++<br />\n* Experience with JUCE (of course)<br />\n* Experience with Objective C<br />\n* Experience with FFGL SDK<br />\n* Experience with openFrameworks or Cinder<br />\n* VJ-ing experience</p>\n<p>This is a full-time position at Resolume HQ in The Hague, The Netherlands. To apply, send a cover letter, your resume and examples of your work to mail@resolume.com Edwin de Koning.</p>\n\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=vAY-bvyRKfg:ETLgAJINAp8:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/vAY-bvyRKfg\" />',1,'2012-04-27 04:46:47','Jobs'),(65,4,'f3257388715fc9e14125b5f44b27e913','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24271','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Patterned by Nature Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Transparent pixels in the North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/h2JupbUmvzo/','','<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Patterned-by-Nature_03.png\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Patterned-by-Nature_03-640x359.png\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p>Some time ago Sosolimited and Plebian DesignÃ‚Â set out to createÃ‚Â a large scale transparent LCD sculpture for a science museum atrium. Each pixel was designed as a piece of glass that could independently change the transparency of: from opaque black to transparent. The sculpture was designed to curve up through the atrium of the museum and display down-sampled patterns from nature, along with a high fidelity soundtrack. Almost two years later, its wonderful to see this project finally come to life<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/c/patterned-by-nature-transparent-pixels-in-the-north-carolina-museum-of-natural-sciences/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_campaign=rss-mo-more&amp;utm_medium=rss\">Continue reading.... Patterned by Nature &#8211; Transparent pixels in the North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences</a></p>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=h2JupbUmvzo:8ODuQLl7c2g:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/h2JupbUmvzo\" />',1,'2012-04-25 15:45:10','Filip'),(66,4,'6b77cbdc9d6c72d76c22d5020a7c2911','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24266','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Interaction Designer for Apps at Scott Snibbe Studio','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/E0MCRZhzvHw/','','<img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/scottsnibbe.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\nCompany:Ã‚Â <a href=\"http://snibbestudio.com/\">Scott Snibbe Studio</a>\n<p>Location: San Francisco, USA<br />\nType:Ã‚Â Interaction Designer<br />\nJob Type:Ã‚Â Full-Time</p>\nDescription\n<p>Scott Snibbe Studio is a pioneer in bringing the emotional impact of movies and music to apps. We believe interactivity is capable of no less than bringing our dreams to life. We create original apps, and also partner with some of the most creative artists in the world including BjÃƒÂ¶rk and James Cameron.</p>\n<p>We are seeking an inventive and visually brilliant interaction designer to join our San Francisco team.</p>\n<p>YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re flexible, playful and as confident as you are skeptical. You know how to look at a nasty problem and efficiently unpack it into manageable parts. You&#8217;re someone who always notices the tiny details and feels physically uncomfortable when you see thoughtless design. You know mobile music and entertainment apps and have a strong sense of how to make them better. YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re fluent in current mobile UI and UX best practices and know when to throw them out the window to make something groundbreaking. We work as a tight cross-disciplinary team, so you should comfortable working closely with engineers, business development staff, producers, designers, filmmakers, musicians, and writers.</p>\n<p>Key responsibilities</p>\n<p>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Take music and entertainment app concepts from pencil sketch, to concept art, proposals, and pixel-perfect design specifications.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ Work closely with our product managers, designers and engineers to define the best way to approach a problem.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ When working with clients, know how to ask the right questions to understand their needs, and transforming them into stylistic treatments, and interaction concepts.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ Create gorgeous visual interaction designs and concept art in a wide variety of styles informed by the history of music, art, and movies.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ Over time, establish and reinforce consistent interaction design patterns across platforms.<br />\nRequirements</p>\n<p>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Passion and ideas about where interactive music and film can go as a medium.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ A portfolio that includes self-started personal projects for which you had total creative control.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ Ability to empathize with a variety of end-users, and carry your insight to their simplest, clearest design expression.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ 3+ years designing experiences across multiple platforms with focus on iOS and Android.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ Solid functional understanding of the technologies behind our work: iOS and Android, interactive animation, interactive music, computer graphics, simulation.<br />\nÃ¢â‚¬Â¢ Strong visual design, illustration, and concept art abilities.<br />\nThis job is based in our San Francisco headquarters. We offer a competitive compensation package including health and dental insurance, stock options, and 401(k) plan participation. Please send a resume, portfolio, and salary requirements to jobs@snibbe.com.</p>\n<p>ABOUT SCOTT SNIBBE STUDIO</p>\n<p>Scott Snibbe Studio is pioneering apps as a new interactive medium with the emotional impact of cinema, yet one where we play an active part in changing, creating, and exploring worlds beneath our fingertips. We produce original, category-defying music, art, and entertainment apps, and partner creatively with musicians, filmmakers, and writers. We believe interactivity is capable of no less than bringing our dreams to life. Our studioÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s work includes the bestselling apps Gravilux, Bubble Harp, OscilloScoop, and BjÃƒÂ¶rkÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Biophilia.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.snibbe.com/blog/2011/10/11/biophilia/\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Biophilia-screenshot-iPad-0-Cosmogony-640x480.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=E0MCRZhzvHw:EGS3e5wFSmk:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/E0MCRZhzvHw\" />',1,'2012-04-25 06:37:16','Jobs'),(67,4,'25f7baca5f13fadaa78a35a3230f3f05','http://www.creativeapplications.net/?p=24247','2012-05-03 18:15:09','Hot Networks Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Complexities and opportunities in collaborative robotics','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~3/8DSMMNmbdfg/','','<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/plastic6.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/plastic6-640x426.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p>Created by Brandon Kruysman and Jonathan Proto,Ã‚Â Hot NetworksÃ‚Â explores the complexities and opportunities in collaborative robotics. Ã‚Â Using custom built software called esperant.O developed by Kruysman-Proto, Hot NetworksÃ‚Â is a collaboration of five industrial robot arms, with different tools and tasks, operating as one large network. Ã‚Â Ideas of representation are embedded into the sequence, as well as materialÃ‚Â behaviour, and synchronous motion and tooling.Ã¯Â¿Â½<p><a href=\"http://www.creativeapplications.net/objects/hot-networks-complexities-and-opportunities-in-collaborative-robotics/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_campaign=rss-mo-more&amp;utm_medium=rss\">Continue reading.... Hot Networks &#8211; Complexities and opportunities in collaborative robotics</a></p>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:V_sGLiPBpWU\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=qj6IDK7rITs\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:gIN9vFwOqvQ\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?i=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?a=8DSMMNmbdfg:t3jyBtN1zCY:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/creativeapplicationsnet?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\"></img></a>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/creativeapplicationsnet/~4/8DSMMNmbdfg\" />',1,'2012-04-24 15:31:00','Filip'),(68,5,'0a6289731753876cea1fb9546feac7da','http://observersroom.designobserver.com/feature/the-visual-language-of-herbert-matter/33988/','2012-05-03 18:16:18',' OBlog: The Visual Language of Herbert Matter','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/designobserver/observersroom/~3/JG13aLrZ1Rg/','','Known as a quintessential designer\'s designer,  Swiss born Herbert  Matter is largely credited with  expanding the use of photography as a  design tool and bringing the  semantics of fine art into the realm of  applied arts.',1,'2012-05-02 15:47:00',''),(69,5,'','http://observersroom.designobserver.com/feature/ex-libris--the-art-of-the-bookplate/33998/','2012-05-03 18:16:18',' OBlog: Ex-Libris : The Art of the Bookplate','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/designobserver/observersroom/~3/0hPnAzEiYTc/','','',1,'2012-05-01 17:07:00',''),(70,5,'a347ea47c40ddbcf78d4f5a0afcba473','http://observersroom.designobserver.com/feature/two-foto-animator/33978/','2012-05-03 18:16:18',' OBlog: Two Foto Animator','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/designobserver/observersroom/~3/xA9gP6Dw8Xc/','','A real life steampunk animated gif.',1,'2012-05-01 08:58:00',''),(71,5,'b8b6c263da1978577852bcc612d35ee3','http://observersroom.designobserver.com/feature/alien-phenomenology-or-what-its-like-to-be-a-thing/33868/','2012-05-03 18:16:18','Rob Walker: Alien Phenomenology: Or, What It\'s Like To Be A Thing','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/designobserver/observersroom/~3/CTanV-P6S8o/','','Recommended Book: Rob Walker recommends <em>Alien Phenomenology: Or, What It\'s Like To Be A Thing</em> by Ian Bogost.',1,'2012-04-27 09:43:00',''),(72,5,'a998e1ab8d2e173207a32d1661fb3282','http://observersroom.designobserver.com/feature/mill-rock-farm/33928/','2012-05-03 18:16:18',' OBlog: Mill Rock Farm','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/designobserver/observersroom/~3/yqFaB92pc98/','','&ldquo;The farmers,&rdquo; wrote the American Statesman Daniel Webster, &ldquo;are the founders of human civilization.\" We think so, too! Please help us by supporting Mill Rock Farm.',1,'2012-04-26 13:01:00',''),(73,5,'aa0190c3fe9ce32d8501baba953cb9bb','http://observersroom.designobserver.com/feature/yoshiko-sato-1960-2012--an-exhibition/33908/','2012-05-03 18:16:18',' OBlog: Yoshiko Sato 1960-2012 : An Exhibition','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/designobserver/observersroom/~3/bGRIrZ8Q5pE/','','An exhibition of Yoshiko Sato\'s work is on view on the 100 and 400 levels of Avery Hall at Columbia University through May 4, 2012.',1,'2012-04-24 17:30:00',''),(74,5,'c4008179bcb7ee0b6342884a575a37c7','http://observersroom.designobserver.com/feature/ideas-that-matter/33558/','2012-05-03 18:16:18',' OBlog: Ideas that Matter','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/designobserver/observersroom/