esigned by <a href=\"http://1trickpony.com\">One Trick Pony</a>\n        \n        Printed by <a href=\"http://www.cardsofwood.com/\">Cards of Wood</a>\n        \n        Finally, we know the real reason why the Log Lady was so inseparable from her clairvoyant friend.\n        \n \n        <img src=\"http://www.underconsideration.com/fpo/project_images/alcoholidays_01.jpg\" alt=\"Alcoholidays Packaging\" />\n\n<img src=\"http://www.underconsideration.com/fpo/project_images/alcoholidays_02.jpg\" alt=\"Alcoholidays Packaging\" />\n\n        Production Details\n        \n        <p>Client<br />\n        <a href=\"http://Yulelogin.com/\">YULE LOGIN</a></p>\n            \n        <p>Quantity Produced<br />\n        300</p>\n        \n        <p>Production Cost<br />\n        $31 per log</p>\n        \n        <p>Production Time<br />\n        2 Months\n            \n        <p>Dimensions (Width &times; Height &times; Depth)<br />\n        &ndash;</p>\n        \n        <p>Page Count<br />\n        &ndash;</p>\n        \n        <p>Paper Stock<br />\n        &ndash;</p>\n        \n        <p>Number of Colors<br />\n        Gold Foil\n        \n        <p>Varnishes<br />\n        &ndash;</p>\n        \n        <p>Binding<br />\n        &ndash;</p>\n        \n        <p>Typopgraphy<br />\n        Custom Version of Atreyu from Losttype.com</p>\n        \n        \n        \n \n        <img src=\"http://www.underconsideration.com/images/advx3_rss_header.gif\" alt=\"Many thanks to our ADVx3 Partners\" />\n<br />\n<a href=\"http://underconsideration.com/oa_x/www/delivery/ck.php?oaparams=2__bannerid=17__zoneid=0__cb=b5cf3b2ed3__oadest=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.neenahpaper.com%2Fclassic%3Futm_campaign%3DUnderConsideration_CLASSIC_OctNov2011%26utm_source%3DBanner\"><img src=\"http://underconsideration.com/oa_x/www/delivery/avw.php?campaignid=3&amp;what=17&amp;cb=INSERT_RANDOM_NUMBER_HERE&amp;n=a8e15125\" /></a>\n\n<a href=\"http://underconsideration.com/oa_x/www/delivery/ck.php?oaparams=2__bannerid=19__zoneid=0__cb=34d6d77ea8__oadest=http%3A%2F%2Fbranding.sva.edu%2F\"><img src=\"http://underconsideration.com/oa_x/www/delivery/avw.php?campaignid=4&amp;what=19&amp;cb=INSERT_RANDOM_NUMBER_HERE&amp;n=a08973cc\" /></a>\n\n<a href=\"http://underconsideration.com/oa_x/www/delivery/ck.php?oaparams=2__bannerid=180__zoneid=0__cb=fff6446e3c__oadest=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sappi.com%2FideasthatmatterNA\"><img src=\"http://underconsideration.com/oa_x/www/delivery/avw.php?campaignid=16&amp;what=180&amp;cb=INSERT_RANDOM_NUMBER_HERE&amp;n=a645fbf4\" /></a>\n\n<a href=\"http://underconsideration.com/oa_x/www/delivery/ck.php?oaparams=2__bannerid=194__zoneid=0__cb=b17ba3efa1__oadest=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.mohawkconnects.com%2F\"><img src=\"http://underconsideration.com/oa_x/www/delivery/avw.php?campaignid=17&amp;what=194&amp;cb=INSERT_RANDOM_NUMBER_HERE&amp;n=a621feb9\" /></a>\n    \n    <img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/ucllc/fpo/~4/tkEc4IsHS9M\" />',1,'2012-05-04 05:23:00','kelly'),(174,1,'3c344a111b512a37cf029e7a57f6ff35','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546342','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Spotify Crop Circle Appears Near Stonehenge','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/YHbiggQ3gLs/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/henge-circle-3.jpeg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"henge circle 3\" />Aliens are streaming our music! A crop circle bearing a striking resemblance to the Spotify logo has appeared in Wiltshire, England near Stonehenge. The <a href=\"http://www.spotify.com/\">Swedish startup</a> denies having anything to do with the formation pressed into a canola seed field.\n\nSirius XM satellite radio must feel a little jealous, as it\'s been beaming music into space for years. Hopefully the extraterrestrials like to party, as Fun.\'s drunken anthem <a href=\"http://open.spotify.com/track/7a86XRg84qjasly9f6bPSD\">\"We Are Young\"</a> has been topping the Spotify charts for weeks. Otherwise, we may need to assemble Will Smith and others with experience fighting aliens.',1,'2012-05-04 13:08:45','Josh Constine'),(175,1,'5cb57b101663b139c51494f82a451623','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546345','2012-05-04 16:06:42','MTV Will Try To Break Guinness Record For Most Live Concerts With O Music Awards','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/waPIp5pt4bo/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/o_music_awards_logo_large.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"o_music_awards_logo_large\" />You\'ve probably heard the complaint that MTV has forgotten its music video roots and spends too much time on reality television. Heck, you may have said something similar yourself. Well, for its third <a href=\"http://www.omusicawards.com\">O Music Awards</a> (an \"event that celebrates and honors the artists, fans and innovators impacting digital music culture\"), MTV combining elements of both Ã¢â‚¬â€ it\'s an awards show, a concert (actually multiple concerts), and a reality TV show about a band hitting the road.\n\nThe previous O Music Awards were held Las Vegas West Hollywood, but this time the show is actually going to be on the road. A yet-to-be-named band will be touring the Mississippi Delta, birthplace of rock, and stop in eight different cities, with the award presentations interspersed. One of the goals is to set a new Guinness World Record for Most Live Concerts in 24 Hours (Multiple Cities) Ã¢â‚¬â€ apparently setting new records is something MTV tries with every show, but this time it\'s really baked into the basic concept. And naturally, all of this will be livestreamed.',1,'2012-05-04 13:06:30','Anthony Ha'),(176,1,'eeaa2601fcadfde041a6438836eae048','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546343','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Lost In The Supermarket? A New Sensor Will Navigate For You Indoors','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/gQYvSpf-qPE/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/pi25_g_navigating-the-shopping-center.jpeg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"pi25_g_navigating-the-shopping-center\" />Sure, GPS helps us get from Point A to Point B, but what if you\'re just trying to find the Cinnabon? A new system from Fraunhofer allows for in-store (or in-mall) navigation and uses very simple sensors to asses where you are in the building at any time.\n\nThe system works when you enter the edifice and scan a QR code. This identifies your current position. A built-in pedometer and compass assess the speed and direction you\'re going and, rather than relying on GPS signals, the system can tell where you are simply based on stride length. \n',1,'2012-05-04 13:05:16','John Biggs'),(177,1,'66a408e797a6a79fde2cc956ef31b8b8','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546320','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Foursquare Gets Its Own Searchable Timeline With New History Page','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/WrgcvtBMn6U/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/history-page.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"history page\" />Foursquare has tweakedÃ‚Â <a href=\"http://foursquare.com/history\">its history page</a>Ã‚Â this morning, in order to give users a more functional, searchable version of their past check-ins. Although you could see your old check-ins before, they weren\'t as accessible as they are now. The new page lets you click on a drop-down box to head back into the previous months or years (somewhatÃ‚Â reminiscentÃ‚Â of Facebook Timeline functionality), while sidebar boxes lets you search and filter your check-ins by location, category or who you were with at the time.',1,'2012-05-04 12:32:40','Sarah Perez'),(178,1,'2b8e0b17908881ae95efef030ce6ba67','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546324','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Surprisingly Simple Arduino Motion-Sensing Project Makes For Some Weekend Fun','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/cy4UcojlPTQ/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/complete.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"complete\" />If you\'ve always wanted to try to build an <a HREF=\"http://techcrunch.com/tag/Arduino\">Arduino</a> project, this may be a great way to start. Matt Williamson built a tiny, Arduino-based motion sensor that will SMS you when something moves by your desk or into a room. It\'s completely open source and the notifications system runs on your PC thanks to a simple Python script.\n',1,'2012-05-04 12:18:55','John Biggs'),(179,1,'7c041a7837350d1f7f7b33f8dac39b6b','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546235','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Please Also Welcome Ryan Lawler, TechCrunchÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Newest New Star Writer','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/BSEHb_NSNmw/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-04-at-12-01-13-pm.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2012-05-04 at 12.01.13 PM\" />We\'ve been writing so many \"<a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/03/02/hi-kim-mai/\">please welcome</a> <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/10/please-welcome-peter-ha-frederic-lardinois-and-new-co-editor-alexia-tsotsis/\">star writer</a>\" posts lately that we\'re having to work hard to think of new versions of that headline. But that\'s the only painful part of this one, as we\'re very excited to announce that pro blogger <a href=\"http://twitter.com/#!/ryanlawler\">Ryan Lawler</a> will be joining the team on Monday.\n\n<a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/?attachment_id=546279\"></a>You might know him for his work over last five years covering various media, telecom, online video, and -- as he made his way from New York to San Francisco with <a href=\"http://gigaom.com\">GigaOM</a> -- startups.',1,'2012-05-04 11:59:55','Contributor'),(180,1,'add3e2573c0d46f7e0930e85d25765c6','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546268','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Why CanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t BlackBerry Muddle Through? TheyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re Not The 99%','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/v4Zobqu436s/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-03-at-5-3-10-33.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2012-05-03-at-5-3-10.33\" />Horace Dediu at <a href=\"http://www.asymco.com/2012/05/03/the-phone-market-in-2012-a-tale-of-two-disruptions/\">Asymco</a> has run the numbers and it\'s not looking good. Samsung and Apple now control an estimated 99% of vendor profits with HTC scraping in with 1%. BlackBerry and Nokia barely register and, in fact, form a loss.\n\nFirst, I\'d like to note why Dediu believes carriers are willing to cede so much of their profit to Apple and, presumably, Samsung. It\'s mostly about lock-in, a sort of bear hug that encourages customers to stay put in the long run. He writes:',1,'2012-05-04 11:59:54','John Biggs'),(181,1,'9f1a040e5b90de94855b7f7157e7aed2','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546259','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Hachi Combines LinkedIn, Facebook, Twitter & Google Into One, Lets You Search All Your Connections At Once','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/6qKIY0bj8wo/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/hachi-logo1.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"hachi-logo\" />OK, this is cool. A new networking utility called <a href=\"https://www.gohachi.com\">Hachi</a> is taking some of the best functionality offered by LinkedIn (searching by name, company, title, etc. and seeing how you\'re connected to other users), and is merging that with your social graphs from other services like Facebook, and soon Google contacts, Twitter and even your Outlook address book. That way, you can see who you know where - meaning, the actual <em>path</em> of connections between you and another person - even if you\'re not connected on LinkedIn.\n\nUm, totally bookmarking this.',1,'2012-05-04 11:42:11','Sarah Perez'),(182,1,'a17735cb7bbadd798022b44a179830a2','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546234','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Calling All Startups: TechCrunch New York Just Posted Office Hours (May 9)','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/RAEVoF130X4/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/officehoursclipart_0.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"OfficeHoursClipArt_0\" />Office Hours in New York was a huge success last week. We met the guys from <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/05/03/krossover-makes-athletes-coaches-smarter-with-business-intelligence-for-sports/\">Krossover</a>, along with quite a few other really badass startups which we\'ll post about when the time comes. That said, I want more. More, more, more. (I\'m greedy like that.)\n\nSo we\'re officially posting our second round of Office Hours. This time, instead of a coffee shop, we\'re hitting startup turf: DUMBO Incubator in Brooklyn.',1,'2012-05-04 11:10:10','Jordan Crook'),(183,1,'fda555f3d85bd365b014bcf60c69b591','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546261','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Apple Finally Gives Proper Credit To OpenStreetMap In iPhoto For iOS','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/w2qGnvkeArg/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/osm_logo.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"osm_logo\" />When Apple launched iPhoto for iPhone, it quickly became clear that there was something odd going on with the maps in the application. Even though Apple never talked about this publicly, the data Apple used to render these new maps was clearly not from Google anymore. Instead, most experts <a href=\"http://spatiallyadjusted.com/2012/03/08/if-apples-map-tiles-use-openstreetmap/\">agreed</a>, Apple was using a number of different sources to create its new map tiles without giving <a href=\"http://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright\">proper credit</a> to groups like <a href=\"http://www.openstreetmap.org/\">OpenStreetMap</a>, the Wikipedia-like crowdsourced mapping organization. This week\'s update to iPhoto for iPhone, however, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/openstreetmap/status/198101512201834497\">finally</a> gives credit where credit is due.',1,'2012-05-04 11:02:16','Frederic Lardinois'),(184,5,'','http://observersroom.designobserver.com/feature/ingenious-solutions-for-simple-needs--01/34068/','2012-05-04 16:06:42',' OBlog: Ingenious Solutions for Simple Needs : 01','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/designobserver/observersroom/~3/-f_HshISm_4/','','',1,'2012-05-04 12:28:00',''),(185,1,'7d740bb0a0a9ba295db65820f4a7a99c','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546192','2012-05-04 16:06:42','TidePool Raises $1.5 Million To Discover And Match Personalities From Photos','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/GZTvkRFebc4/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/tide2.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"tide2\" /><a href=\"http://www.tidepool.co/\">TidePool</a>, a startup that is trying to determine consumer personality from photos, has raised $1.5 million in a seed round led by Mike Hirshland of Resolute.VC and Michael Dearing of Harrison Metal Capital. Participating investors include Jarl Mohn, Tim Draper, Peggy and Jim Davis, and Jeff Lipp.\n\nThe startup\'s central goal is simpleÃ¢â‚¬â€Tidepool uses a proprietary technology to uncover personality and other psychological characteristics from photos. To begin your assessment on Tidepool, you are presented a number of photos. You are asked to rank photos by which ones you like best. You are also asked to pick between two images that you like, choose different interests (based on pictures) and more.',1,'2012-05-04 10:08:51','Leena Rao'),(186,1,'c7604bddc72db72881570acd2c3249c7','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546193','2012-05-04 16:06:42','HTC Titan II Review: Head-To-Head With The Lumia 900 And One X','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/-vuGnJoew5o/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-04-at-10-27-43-am.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen shot 2012-05-04 at 10.27.43 AM\" />The <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/05/01/fly-or-die-htc-titan-ii/\">HTC Titan II has already gone through the Fly or Die ringer</a>, but the real determining factor for these phones is the level of competition surrounding them. In the case of the <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/27/htc-titan-ii-review-initial-impressions-hands-on-photos/\">Titan II</a>, the HTC/Microsoft partnership is most threatened by more HTC and Windows-powered phones, namely the Lumia 900 and the HTC One X.\n\nSo what do these phones have that the Titan lacks? How does the Titan wipe up the floor with them?\n\nWell, that\'s why I\'m here, and why we\'ve made this lovely graphic for you. \n',1,'2012-05-04 10:08:32','Jordan Crook'),(187,1,'287e1f9f075bac2f25fa9541e2acd470','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546223','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Startups.com Is Shutting Down, Domain Name Not For Sale (For Now)','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/AEsVdEELAWM/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/startups.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"startups\" />Daily deal community for website owners <a href=\"http://www.startups.com\">Startups.com</a> is shutting down. In an email sent out to its mailing list subscribers, founder Gonzo Arzuaga admits that the company just \"couldn\'t make a go of it.\"\n\n\"We didn\'t achieve the ambitious goals we set for ourselves when we launched only 1 year ago. So, with regret, this news of our departure fromÃ‚Â the realm of Daily Deals,\" writes Arzuaga. \"This may be a shocker to some of you and we want you to know that we\'re really sorry we failed to achieve your expectations.\"',1,'2012-05-04 10:04:48','Sarah Perez'),(188,2,'95f5baf876b86f23e27bf4e5ec8ba124','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/att-randall-stephenson/','2012-05-04 16:06:42','AT&T Chief Regrets Offering Unlimited Data for iPhone','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/att-randall-stephenson/','','Randall Stephenson, AT&#38;T\'s chief executive, spoke about the state of the wireless industry at a conference this week, and he shared some surprisingly frank comments about the iPhone. He said he loses sleep over services like iMessage.',1,'2012-05-04 15:25:32','By BRIAN X. CHEN'),(189,2,'ba3247ebcf82d8895cffe84a7060ab90','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/dont-be-shocked-by-more-big-acquisitions-facebook-says/','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Don\'t Be Shocked by More Big Acquisitions, Facebook Says','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/dont-be-shocked-by-more-big-acquisitions-facebook-says/','','In a roadshow video, Facebook says it is likely to make more expensive investments to rev up its mobile presence. The video devotes considerable time to convince investors that advertising, which is Facebook\'s principal revenue source, is a promising business.',1,'2012-05-04 11:55:54','By SOMINI SENGUPTA'),(190,2,'6eec898edeb02a9fb9d81162a9bab0ce','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/daily-report-small-investors-may-get-a-piece-of-facebook/','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Daily Report: Small Investors May Get a Piece of Facebook','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/daily-report-small-investors-may-get-a-piece-of-facebook/','','Typically, shares of hot initial public offerings go almost entirely to the biggest clients of the Wall Street banks that oversee the stock sale. But as Susanne Craig and Evelyn M. Rusli report in Friday\'s New York Times, Facebook\'s executives and underwriters have discussed raising the number of shares that will go to small investors.',1,'2012-05-04 07:44:02','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(191,2,'e2df35d84fe965e993cb910d7041998d','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/u-s-study-cites-worries-on-readiness-for-cyberattacks/','2012-05-04 16:06:42','U.S. Study Cites Worries on Readiness for Cyberattacks','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/u-s-study-cites-worries-on-readiness-for-cyberattacks/','','A report assessing the nation\'s ability to respond to terrorist attacks and various disasters found that state and local officials are the most concerned about dealing with cyberattacks. <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/us/politics/study-finds-concerns-on-readiness-for-cyberattacks.html?ref=technology\">Read more &#187;</a>',1,'2012-05-04 07:26:44','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(192,2,'afaa9e35c2256be6a996ea4f80a82ada','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/taking-e-mail-vacations-can-reduce-stress-study-says/','2012-05-04 16:06:42','Taking E-Mail Vacations Can Reduce Stress, Study Says','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/taking-e-mail-vacations-can-reduce-stress-study-says/','','A study released Thursday found that people who do not look at e-mail on a regular basis at work are less stressed about their daily tasks and are more productive.',1,'2012-05-04 05:00:16','By NICK BILTON'),(193,1,'12862b3ea5529e1a4919bd5c744ad5e9','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546749','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Is This Censorship? Facebook Stops You From Posting Ã¢â‚¬ËœIrrelevant Or InappropriateÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ Comments','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/RUT3WDTBGzo/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-05-at-4-51-28-pm.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2012-05-05 at 4.51.28 PM\" />Updated. Today was just another Saturday morning in blog land when <a href=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/person/robert-scoble\">Robert Scoble</a>, the well-known tech startup enthusiast, went to post a comment on a <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/max.woolf/posts/326466947419794\">Facebook post</a> written by Carnegie Mellon student (and TechCrunch commenter extraordinaire) <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/max.woolf\">Max Woolf</a> about the nature of today\'s tech blogging scene. Scoble\'s comment itself was pretty par-for-the-course -- generally agreeing with Woolf\'s sentiments and adding in his own two cents.\n\nBut when Scoble went to click post, he <a href=\"https://plus.google.com/111091089527727420853/posts/cdZQPUiMp9b\">received an</a> odd error message:',1,'2012-05-05 14:31:07','Colleen Taylor'),(194,1,'3664592a2cb9aa1c0c5ab23613f10383','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546710','2012-05-05 15:00:55','If Facebook Could Enter China, Here Are Some Of The Hurdles','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/rFOiQfyM0S4/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/greatfirewall1.jpeg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"greatfirewall1\" />Mark ZuckerbergÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s visit to China back in December 2011 created a storm of speculation on whether Facebook was preparing for a full scale entry into the most populous country in the world. Photos of Zuckerberg visiting SinaÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s headquarters in Beijing, leaked by a Sina employee and reports of him meeting with other major Chinese Internet companies such as Baidu and Alibaba have further fueled rumors that Facebook is looking for a local partner to facilitate its China entry.\n\nPutting aside the rumors and speculation, there is little doubt that Facebook is looking for a way to enter the China market and the real questions lie not in the Ã¢â‚¬Å“if,Ã¢â‚¬Â but rather the Ã¢â‚¬Å“how,Ã¢â‚¬Â Ã¢â‚¬Å“whenÃ¢â‚¬Â and whether Facebook will be able to make a success of their China market entry when countless other western Internet juggernauts have bruised and battered themselves against the Great firewall of China.',1,'2012-05-05 14:00:00','Contributor'),(195,1,'f4510afd2bf6a143bfac1e8fe62e5e00','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546728','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Nathan Myhrvold, ex-MSFT CTO And Patent Powerbroker, Gobbles Up A Major Cookbook Award','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/QGz8CRwrQ_M/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-05-at-18-55-45.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"modernist cuisine myhrvold\" />Nathan Myhrvold, erstwhile Microsoft CTO and now patentÃ‚Â powerbroker extraordinare, has hit the news this weekend, but it\'s not for his latest licensing deal with a <a href=\"http://www.intellectualventures.com/newsroom/pressreleases/11-11-08/LG_Electronics_Enters_License_Agreement_with_Intellectual_Ventures.aspx\">mobile phone maker</a>, or for a lawsuit against a <a href=\"http://www.geekwire.com/2011/intellectual-ventures-sues-nikon-patent-infringement/\">tech company</a> (or <a href=\"http://www.intellectualventures.com/NewsRoom/NewsCoverage/12-02-16/Patent_Collector_Intellectual_Ventures_Sues_AT_T_Sprint_and_T-Mobile_for_Infringement.aspx\">three</a>) that refuses to pay up for patents that his company, <a href=\"http://www.intellectualventures.com/\">Intellectual Ventures</a>, owns -- but for a different kettle of fish altogether.\n\nMyhrvold has won the <a href=\"http://www.jamesbeard.org/blog/2012-jbf-book-broadcast-journalism-awards-recap\">James Beard Foundation book award for cookbook of the year</a> -- the top prize in one of the industry\'s most prestigious accolades -- for a book that deep-dives, appropriately enough, into the science and technology of cooking.\n\nHis book, the self-publishedÃ‚Â <a href=\"http://modernistcuisine.com/\">Modernist Cuisine</a>, is a six-volume,Ã‚Â 2,438-page effort that he co-wrote with Chris Young and Maxime Bilet (and a 20-person team of cooks), which is selling for $625 (or $455.11 on <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Modernist-Cuisine-The-Science-Cooking/dp/0982761007\">Amazon</a>).',1,'2012-05-05 13:05:20','Ingrid Lunden'),(196,1,'7dde65f91f342d1e0efc76eb06f60451','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546734','2012-05-05 15:00:55','With A Talent War In The Valley, Perhaps Romania Has The Answers?','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/SKiIVH1ru6I/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/bucharest-capital-of-romania.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Bucharest-capital-of-romania\" />Today, in 2012, there is a talent war like no other. The Valley is abuzz with a hiring frenzy. Startups can\'t compete with Yammer, Zynga, Twitter, Facebook and the rest for developers. Perhaps the answer is to look elsewhere? To countries where the old Soviet education system produced maths and science graduates by the truckload? To Kiev, Belgrade, Slovenia and others? And perhaps to Romania.\n\nFor Romanians, perhaps for the first time in history, the world is now flat. Forty-five years of Stalin-esque communism meant sports and education were the only acceptable ways to compete in Romania. Soviet-era industrialisation ended up producing a country where almost half of the educated population were trained to become engineers. Today, in 2012, they are more likely to be coders. And now they can take their place with the rest of the world on the level playing field of technology.',1,'2012-05-05 12:46:19','Contributor'),(221,3,'a7dae75dc0019e2398140eee1d2e3c1d','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16684','2012-05-06 10:54:37','The Reading Room at Grand Union','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16684','','<p><a href=\"http://www.grand-union.org.uk/project-space/current-/\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/reading-room_background.jpg\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.grand-union.org.uk/project-space/current-/\">The Reading Room</a></p>\n<p>Founded by by artists CiarÃƒÂ¡n Walsh and Dominique Hurth, <a href=\"http://www.thereadingroom-index.com/\">The Reading Room</a> is a project based in Berlin, with the aim to maintain, archive and represent products of contemporary art practices evolving within printed and published formats. The Reading Room presents a curated selection of over 75 artist&#8217;s publications (books, zines, magazines and newspapers) and related projects (such as fold-out posters or published audio projects), from a range of internationally based artists, both established and emerging.</p>\n<p>In addition to the traditionally known artist-made books, artist monographs or exhibition catalogues, the published format itself is now regularly viewed as a primary site for an artist&#8217;s engagement. While often considered as secondary to the more prevalent presentation space of the gallery, the act of publishing has developed itself into a self-contained and highly resonant method of artistic expression. The Reading Room focuses on the publication utilised as medium and context for art practices, in which the artists choose deliberately and critically to engage with the format, using its materiality, edges and frame as tools for both visual and semantic communication.</p>\n<p>For this exhibition at Grand Union, their collection will displayed dynamically according to six curatorial axes, exploring the spectrum of relationships between conceptual content, physical publication formats and the experience of the Reader. Grand Union will also show a programme of screen based works that expand on these ideas and the act of reading.</p>\n<p>May 19 &#8211; June 23<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.grand-union.org.uk\">Grand Union</a>, Birmingham</p>\n',1,'2012-05-06 01:34:51','manystuff'),(197,1,'835984a1aef36798dd323365ebc1f274','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546556','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Gillmor Gang: The UnLike Filter','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/D95faZImKiw/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2011/08/gillmore-gang-test-pattern.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Gillmor Gang test pattern\" />The Gillmor Gang Ã¢â‚¬â€ Doc Searls, Robert Scoble, John Taschek, Kevin Marks, and Steve Gillmor Ã¢â‚¬â€ surfed the Social Holodeck for signs of intelligent life and overload. Meanwhile: @scobleizer and his Facebook UnLike engine, @dsearls and the Intention Economy, @kevinmarks on the patents protection racket.\n\nIf @jtaschek is right, the Facebook IPO will unleash a startup spending spree the likes of which we\'ve never seen. But what I\'m waiting for is the app to end all apps, or at least autodelete an old one every time I download a new one. Now that will be an algorithm to apply to the push notification queue.\n',1,'2012-05-05 12:00:03','Steve Gillmor'),(198,1,'85f47b05b4c2fc17c5bcc73aac535134','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546630','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Jailbreaking the Degree','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/Nsl9dWtFmtQ/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/alcatraz_dawn_2005-01-07.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Alcatraz_dawn_2005-01-07\" /><p>Jailbreak <em>verb</em>. 1 To get out of a restricted mode of operation. 2 To enable use of a product not intended by the manufacturer.</p>\nCurrently, the degree is the only meaningful Ã¢â‚¬Å“unitÃ¢â‚¬Â of education to which employers give any credence. Of this dependency, <a href=\"http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1967580,00.html\">TIME magazine</a> writes, Ã¢â‚¬Å“The tight connection between college degrees and economic success may be a nearly unquestioned part of our social order. Future generations may look back and shudder at the cruelty of itÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ It is inefficient, both because it wastes a lot of money and because it locks people who would have done good work out of some jobs.Ã¢â‚¬Â',1,'2012-05-05 11:00:33','Contributor'),(199,1,'3e4aa71f4dba6f01414d960efe1a7d3f','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546706','2012-05-05 15:00:55','HTC WonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Hook Up One X Owners With Bootloader Unlock','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/lnQk88QbSn8/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/attonex.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"attonex\" />HTC won over some hearts a while back when it released its <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2011/08/15/htc-finally-offers-bootloader-unlock-u-s-users-must-wait/\">bootloader unlock tool</a> for a good number of devices. It basically allows owners of Android phones to load custom ROMs onto their phones in exchange for any warranty rights they may have been enjoying. \n\nIt\'s a fair trade considering a solid percentage of Android power users prefer Android based mostly on the fact that they have this option, but without solid hardware the ability to load different versions of Androids becomes less and less appealing. \n\nAnd so is the case with the <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/05/04/some-guys-have-all-the-luck-htc-one-x-hitting-doorsteps-ahead-of-schedule/\">HTC One X</a>. It\'s an excellent handset, and possibly the best HTC has ever made. But unfortunately, the company won\'t be offering the bootloader unlock tool for this particular handset. ',1,'2012-05-05 10:49:11','Jordan Crook'),(200,1,'907616294992ead01d4aa2af11c3ed40','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546566','2012-05-05 15:00:55','ZocDoc Rolls Out In Tampa Bay; Says Gen Y Is Clueless About Health Care','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/WKQdQ3kjOgo/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/01/zocdoc1.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"zocdoc\" /><a href=\"http://www.zocdoc.com/\">ZocDoc</a>, the professional booking platform for doctors, is rolling out to another market as of this week: Tampa, Florida - and incidentally, company CEOÃ‚Â Cyrus Massoumi also happens to be a Florida native. But that\'s not why Tampa was chosen as the next major metro area to join the lineup of ZocDoc\'s regions served - the company says that it chooses new markets based on demand from both patients and doctors alike.\n\nIn conjunction with the launch, ZocDoc also released the findings from a new survey it commissioned which highlights why ZocDoc happens to be in such demand: it\'s solving the frustrating problem of finding a doctor and booking an appointment - something which the youngest generation of patients is apparently the most ill-equipped to handle, at least according to the findings.',1,'2012-05-05 10:00:47','Sarah Perez'),(201,1,'2ae1c33dbb51c871f34bf44111924643','http://techcrunch.com/?p=544076','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Cometh The Hour, Cometh The Xobot','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/kg1owvikJAw/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/monodroid.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"monodroid\" /><a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/?attachment_id=544097\"></a>Poor old Android is having a bad year. (Especially compared to <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2011/12/31/freight-train-kept-a-rollin/\">last year</a>.) Apple\'s iPhone is <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/24/apples-iphone-sales-in-china-are-up-by-fivefold-from-a-year-ago/\">soaring in China</a>, and apparently <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/26/apple-will-one-day-rule-the-world/\">overtaking Android</a> in the crucial American market. Oracle\'s lawsuit against Google has led to several rather awkward claims, eg that the word \'license\' in the phrase \"we need to negotiate a license for Java under the terms we need\" <a href=\"http://www.electronista.com/articles/12/04/19/lindholm.says.google.didnt.mean.it.owed.money/\">referred to</a> \"not a license from anybody\", a kind of license with which I was previously entirely unfamiliar. CEO Larry Page\'s own testimony was <a href=\"http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-oracle-page-20120419,0,401138.story\">labelled as</a> evasive: \"His denial of knowledge and recollection contrasts with evidence,\" wrote <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florian_M%C3%BCller\">Florian Mueller</a> of <a href=\"http://fosspatents.com/\">FOSS Patents</a>.\n\nWhat a headache. Way back in 2005, Android head honcho Andy Rubin wrote in a <a href=\"http://java.dzone.com/news/key-emails-could-be-evidence\">prescient email</a>:\n\n<blockquote>Ã¢â‚¬Å“If Sun doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t want to work with us, we have two options: 1) Abandon our work and adopt MSFT CLR VM and C# language Ã¢â‚¬â€œ or Ã¢â‚¬â€œ 2) Do Java anyway and defend our decision, perhaps making enemies along the way.Ã¢â‚¬Â</blockquote>\n\nJust imagine if they\'d taken the first road. It\'s not widely understood in the industry that Microsoft\'s .NET <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Language_Infrastructure\">infrastructure</a> is more open than Java in many ways; it and its flagship language C# are ISO and ECMA standards, available to anyone and everyone, legally bulletproofed by the <a href=\"http://www.microsoft.com/interop/cp/default.mspx\">Microsoft Community Promise</a>. Imagine if the Android OS ran on an entirely different technical architecture.\n\nWait, no. Don\'t imagine it: examine it. Like a vision from a parallel universe, it now exists.\n',1,'2012-05-05 08:00:01','Jon Evans'),(202,1,'f071e409be2ba7b4524a3bd553aa72d2','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546698','2012-05-05 15:00:55','WappwolfÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Automator Now Connects/Syncs Google Drive, Dropbox And Others','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/usHHSNMuaaA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/91976v2-max-250x250.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"91976v2-max-250x250\" />Previously we\'ve <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2011/12/30/dropbox-automator-is-like-ifttt-for-dropbox/\">covered</a> <a href=\"http://wappwolf.com/dropboxautomator\">Dropbox Automator</a>, a sort of <a href=\"http://ifttt.com/\">IFTTT</a> for Dropbox. (IFTTT, if you haven\'t heard, automates tasks to trigger when a particular action has occurred, e.g. if a Facebook profile picture changes, then update a Twitter profile, etc). Like IFTTT, Dropbox Automator is capable of triggering a similar series of actions, based on what kind of files have been added to your Dropbox folders. Now, the startup that makes Dropbox Automator, Wappwolf, has produced <a href=\"http://www.wappwolf.com/gdriveautomator\">Google Drive Automator</a>.',1,'2012-05-05 06:32:03','Mike Butcher'),(203,1,'0f21f4b29207308e780baad2525f4d10','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546672','2012-05-05 15:00:55','New OrleansÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ First Tech Incubator, Launch Pad Ignition, Debuts Its Second Batch Of Startups','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/iSAq7J-mhvA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-04-at-9-58-47-pm.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen shot 2012-05-04 at 9.58.47 PM\" /><a href=\"http://launchpadignition.com/\">Launch Pad Ignition</a>, the first tech incubator to make its home in the Big Easy, today officially unveiled the seven companies that participated in its second annual session. \n\nThe accelerator\'s 12-week program began the second week of February and culminated yesterday with its own New Orleans rendition of the patented \"Demo Day,\" appropriately called \"Launch Fest,\" which we\'ve been told is \"Jazz Fest plus startups, on steroids.\" Launch Pad\'s model is a bit different than that of the traditional accelerator, in that Co-founder <a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/cschultz\">Chris Schultz</a> tells us it\'s geared towards building traction, not offering big early funding.',1,'2012-05-05 01:22:48','Rip Empson'),(204,1,'bd2c2a94b24afe3831659abb81c7a7ca','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546677','2012-05-05 15:00:55','New Start Up CodeNow.Com Lets You Build And Test Code In Real Time, In Your Browser','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/H-bEMHpEkws/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-05-at-2-11-43-am.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2012-05-05 at 2.11.43 AM\" />Trying new APIs is tricky. You can spend hours setting things up, gaining permissions, and learning syntax before you even get to write one line of code. That\'s why <a HREF=\"http://www.codenow.com/\">CodeNow.com</a> is cool. In short, it allows you to try APIs before you invest too much time into them and, as an added bonus, it acts as a code repository.\n\nThe site is currently in private beta but it\'s accepting users tonight.',1,'2012-05-05 01:21:57','John Biggs'),(205,1,'719050521cc8fa5cf052d44251e75d25','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546542','2012-05-05 15:00:55','The Rise of Big Data Apps And The Fall of SaaS','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/eE13LsBzhKI/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/rise_and_fall_03.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"rise_and_fall_03\" />With the influx of information flooding the web Ã¢â‚¬â€œ 90% of the web having been created in the last two years alone Ã¢â‚¬â€œ web businesses are looking for ways to understand and use big data to drive their business. Just as SaaS and the cloud completely revolutionized the way businesses operate, so will Big Data applications (BDAs). BDAs are web-based applications that interpret and use massive amounts of enterprise and web-scale data to deliver more intelligent results for their subscribers. BDAs leverage the best of the cloud; theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re web-hosted, multi-tenant and use Hadoop, noSQL and a range of recommendation and machine learning technologies.\n\nBut the real question is Ã¢â‚¬â€œ so what? So what if the underlying data structures use Hadoop or noSQL? No CEO of a major business gets excited about a value proposition around more scalable data structures. ThatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s where BDAs come in. BDAs donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t just repackage your data in a cool interface or offer productivity improvements in data scalability, they harness the worldÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s data to deliver you a better outcome Ã¢â‚¬â€œ like more revenue.',1,'2012-05-05 00:00:48','Contributor'),(206,1,'6ce974f3956dad1f23ac2e920ea3e598','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546587','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Facebook Likes Just Got Cray Cray','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/DoT27dsX0Ss/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-04-at-7-47-55-pm.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen shot 2012-05-04 at 7.47.55 PM\" />In light of its impending multi-billion-dollar IPO, its user base of 900 million and its increasingly sprawling design and user experience, some people have come to believe that Facebook has gone crazy. Excuse me, \"cray cray.\" \n\nWhat\'s more, even though it\'s only two-odd years old, Facebook\'s \"Like\" button is now ubiquitous on the Webs. But with how quickly these young people are picking up new technology these days, let\'s be honest, \"Liking\" things is for old people. Everyone else has moved on.\n\nThat\'s why Ben Schaechter, Sam Grossberg, and Paul Kompfner have coded up a new Chrome extension, which went live this evening, called CrayBook. (<a href=\"https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/omglgklfnoeapahiopaoidoeagddcinb\">Check it out in the Chrome Web Store here</a>.) ',1,'2012-05-04 23:02:13','Rip Empson'),(207,1,'4d79612908e6306b5dbc85a054bd920e','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546589','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Facebook Buys Location-Based Discovery App Glancee','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/lUBSDM6n7qs/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/screen-shot-2012-05-04-at-6-26-10-pm.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2012-05-04 at 6.26.10 PM\" />A little under one month after its acquisition of Instagram, Facebook has acquired Highlight competitor and ambient location app Glancee.\n\nThe company has already shut down the developerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s passive location app. All three co-founders, GlanceeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s only full-time employees, will join Facebook, which now owns its technology. Our editor Eric Eldon called Glancee, Ã¢â‚¬Å“A nice-guy ambient social location app for normal peopleÃ¢â‚¬Â, so itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s ideas and founders should fit in well building for FacebookÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s mainstream user base.\n',1,'2012-05-04 20:27:36','Alexia Tsotsis'),(208,1,'f1b239135fda49d1739f5376c9fd3c6f','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546554','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Want A Free Desk In SF? i/o Ventures Is Offering Space For Three Startups','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/me5oPmMx81A/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/io_ventures_logo.jpg?w=100&amp;h=49&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"logo\" />I don\'t want to become the publicity arm for every tech organization throwing a contest or giveaway, but once in a while, something comes along that <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/24/one-sentence-pitch-winners/\">seems like a perfect fit</a> for a big chunk of TechCrunch readers. For example: <a href=\"http://ventures.io/\">i/o Ventures</a>, the co-working space and startup incubator based in the Mission District (that\'s San Francisco\'s best neighborhood, for those of you not in the know), is offering free desk space to three startups.\n\nIf you\'re interested, it\'s pretty easy to apply. ',1,'2012-05-04 17:57:06','Anthony Ha'),(209,1,'f07645b8854cce63b05ecbccd412ed95','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546455','2012-05-05 15:00:55','ChoicePass Launches Android App: Think Yelp App For Corporate Perks','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/1iAikUczlhA/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/androidapp-1.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"androidAPP-1\" /><a href=\"http://www.choicepass.com\">ChoicePass</a> is bringing its corporate perk management platform to smartphones starting today, with the launch of <a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.choicepass.corporate\">its Android app</a>.\n\nCo-founder Kyle Hui says his goal is to \"make HR sexy again.\" Specifically that means helping small companies participate in perks programs that they couldn\'t afford on their own, while moving larger companies\' perks into the cloud, freeing them from corporate intranet pages that no one knows about or uses. It\'s a similar in a lot of ways to what <a href=\"http://www.betterworks.com\">BetterWorks</a> is <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/23/betterworks-groups-permissions/\">trying to accomplish</a>, but Hui says that since BetterWorks doesn\'t have mobile apps (yet), this is a big differentiator.',1,'2012-05-04 17:21:05','Anthony Ha'),(210,1,'5445f3d590e86e996df79eabab1a7507','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546500','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Meet Our TC NYC Meet-Up Volunteers','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/S0sZbsYy7is/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/volunteers.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"volunteers\" />This is important, so listen up. \n\nThe people I\'m about to describe are the most awesome of all the awesome people as they have volunteered to help out (free of charge) with our <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/29/the-techcrunch-meet-up-in-nyc-is-officially-official-rsvp-now/\">massive meet-up here in NYC next week</a>. It\'ll be amazing. \n\nLet me paint you a little word picture:',1,'2012-05-04 16:40:54','Jordan Crook'),(211,2,'e3c76b9254be8fc883100fb3774d830e','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/todays-scuttlebot-wiretapping-the-web-and-the-app-lottery/','2012-05-05 15:00:55','Today\'s Scuttlebot: Wiretapping the Web, and the App Lottery','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/todays-scuttlebot-wiretapping-the-web-and-the-app-lottery/','','The technology reporters and editors of The New York Times scour the Web for important and peculiar items. Friday\'s selection includes a Facebook founder criticizing a plan to finance entrepreneurs who don\'t have ideas yet, a report that Verizon salespeople favor Android phones over iPhones and numbers from Facebook.',1,'2012-05-04 17:31:45','By THE NEW YORK TIMES'),(212,2,'448fb6b4f0f0221f958b916712ba7b63','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/roflcon-the-internet-goes-offline-to-talk-web-culture/','2012-05-05 15:00:55','ROFLCon: The Internet Goes Offline to Talk Web Culture','http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/roflcon-the-internet-goes-offline-to-talk-web-culture/','','What makes something a meme? Or perhaps more importantly, what causes a meme to go viral or even mainstream? Authenticity and spontaneity, says Jonathan Zittrain, a law professor at Harvard who studies the Internet and how people use it. He gave the opening keynote speech at ROFLCon, a conference focused on Internet culture.',1,'2012-05-04 16:59:20','By JENNA WORTHAM'),(213,1,'bc27ab02801505ea86afa1fe57ddbceb','http://techcrunch.com/?p=543756','2012-05-06 10:54:35','Under New JOBS Act, More IPO Prospects Consider Filing Confidentially','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/DOiCfnznAX0/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/ipo.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"ipo\" /><a href=\"http://www.solarcity.com/\">SolarCity</a>, the cleantech company backed by Tesla and SpaceX CEO Elon Musk, filed for an IPO this past week. But there\'s hardly been a peep about it compared to most offerings.\n\nThat\'s because under the recently passed JOBS Act, SolarCity didn\'t have to publicly share anything about its financial performance when it filed. This is unlike LinkedIn and Pandora, which had to publicly release three years of data in filings that were more than 150 pages long. In SolarCity\'s case, the company <a href=\"http://www.marketwatch.com/story/solarcity-plans-to-conduct-registered-initial-public-offering-of-its-common-stock-2012-04-30?trk_model=open_graph_object&#38;trk_pos=16&#38;trk_len=7&#38;trk_event=search_ac\">merely put out a two-paragraph statement</a> saying that it had confidentially filed with the SEC and planned to have an IPO.\n\nThis is the new world under <a href=\"http://thomas.loc.gov/home/gpoxmlc112/h3606_enr.xml#toc-H9274444768FD4077878886C2ADD75A61\">the JOBS Act, which was hastily passed last month</a>. SolarCity <a href=\"http://www.mofo.com/files/Uploads/Images/JOBS_Act_Chart.pdf\">qualifies as an \"emerging growth\" company</a>, or one that\'s had less than $1 billion in total revenues in the most recent year.',1,'2012-05-06 10:00:30','Kim-Mai Cutler'),(214,1,'f6042afcfc27ff3b45b946b23c4aea86','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546886','2012-05-06 10:54:35','7 New Educational Startups Founded By Minorities in Tech','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/7jsReIeLLx4/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/800px-math_lecture_at_tkk.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"800px-Math_lecture_at_TKK\" />One of today\'s most challenging yet promising markets is the educational system. If you want to see startups hungry to disrupt an industry, look no further. Founders are trying to solve the problems plaguing our education system: including reconciling student debt, providing students with the skills required to land a job both before and after graduation, and offering the best course material online regardless of age, location and educational level.\n\nMillions of people are headed to the Internet to learn. And now everyone, from professors to entrepreneurs, are looking to launch a platform to solve the problem of a broken traditional educational system  -- And many believe that Silicon Valley will have the answers.',1,'2012-05-06 09:04:30','Contributor'),(215,1,'05299a78a21a1754a30bae3373682a47','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546872','2012-05-06 10:54:35','Startups Live & Die by These 5 Street-Smart Laws of Advertising','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/RZglvrqOd2Y/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/d97ba5987ae3a4572833e96436889e7e1.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"d97ba5987ae3a4572833e96436889e7e\" />Ã¢â‚¬Å“Money alone isn\'t enough to bring happiness . . . happiness [is] when you\'re actually truly ok with losing everything you have.Ã¢â‚¬Â - Tony Hsieh, Delivering Happiness: A Path to Profits, Passion, and Purpose\n\nDisclaimer: This articleÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s sole purpose is to address the core principles of advertising in a new and edgy Ã‚Â way. This is not for the faint of heart or those highly sensitive to socially charged public issues. So suck it Ã‚Â up and buckle up. YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re about to be taken to school (of hard knocks). Class is now in session.',1,'2012-05-06 04:00:49','Contributor'),(216,1,'cb1d6460669c6123985d89d140fddb65','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546820','2012-05-06 10:54:35','Pair vs. Pair: Pair The App Is Getting Sued By Pair Networks, The Hosting Company','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/sq_Okv5Bch0/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/pair3-23-123.png?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"pair3.23.123\" />It was <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/05/01/yuri-milner-dave-morin-sv-angel-crunchfund-and-more-hook-up-pair-with-4-2m/\">less than a week ago</a> that Tenthbit, the developers of the buzzy, new social-networking-app-for-couples (or other partners) <a href=\"http://www.trypair.com\">Pair</a>, picked up a $4.2 million seed round, money the founders said would be used to expand its mobile development and design teams. Now it looks like some of those funds might also need to go to legal bills.\n\nTenthbit is getting sued by <a href=\"http://www.pair.com\">pair Networks</a>, a hosting and domain registration company based in Pittsburgh, for trademark infringement.\n\nTenthbit, meanwhile, has also sued pair Networks, to prevent the other suit from going ahead. Pair Networks is asking for an injunction on Pair the app, as well as \"other relief as this Court deems appropriate.\" Tenthbit argues the two do not compete directly, and would therefore not result in any brand confusion.',1,'2012-05-05 21:20:48','Ingrid Lunden'),(217,1,'2477c5ba06888c55ca3ba503bb39405c','http://techcrunch.com/?p=542769','2012-05-06 10:54:35','San Francisco Mayor Ed Lee On Shifting Tech Hubs Into Urban Centers [TCTV]','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/PbH7tZBpbC0/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/sanfranciscoskyline.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"sanfranciscoskyline\" />For years, companies have been known to flock more to SF\'s southern suburbs or to San Jose some 50 miles south, where space is often cheaper and the tax situation has historically been more lax. But surrounded by tech-focused supporters <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2011/10/25/ron-conway-marissa-mayer-mc-hammer-and-others-endorse-sf-mayoral-candidate-ed-lee-in-amazingly-silly-video/\">such as Ron Conway and Marissa Mayer</a>, Ed Lee has made it a major priority of his administration to bring more technological innovation and startup businesses into the city of San Francisco. ',1,'2012-05-05 21:00:48','Colleen Taylor'),(218,1,'8d25020901e26fc7ad7b5dbebdb9cd07','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546803','2012-05-06 10:54:35','Putting Plans to Work: Best Practices for Hackathon Demo Days','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/CFfOBGckAN8/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/6811048668_3ddace1f17_b.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"6811048668_3ddace1f17_b\" />For anyone who enjoys (or has a knack for) planning, <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/03/31/hackathon-planning/\">organizing a hackathon</a> is not terribly difficult: itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a matter of understanding your goals, assessing needs, and figuring out how to bridge the two. Naturally, this is much easier said than done.\n\nThe most important part of a hackathon, by far, are the demos. Why else -- itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s what makes the event worth attending in the first place. Sponsoring companies wouldnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t offer money to anything that didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t provide exposure. Developers wouldnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t forsake sleep if they couldnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t show an eager audience the hacks they built overnight.\n\nPulling off demos at <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/31793064\">Photo Hack Day</a> and <a href=\"http://www.betabeat.com/2012/02/21/aviary-photo-hack-day-two-general-assembly-berlin-02212012/\">Photo Hack Day 2</a>, for example, has proven to be a continuous learning process, with a much more public (and much less forgiving) learning curve. ThereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s no need to be a n00b, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve done a lot of the screwing up for you.',1,'2012-05-05 18:00:28','Contributor'),(219,1,'4d060ea8d787b9fe0b5c2721c7196aba','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546796','2012-05-06 10:54:35','Facebook Says TodayÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Comment Limitations Are Due To Spam Filter, Not Censorship','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/mJltPRomyag/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/4634002184_b8e1cc16fc_z.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"4634002184_b8e1cc16fc_z\" />An automated Facebook spam filter, not purposeful censorship, is to blame for startup enthusiast Robert Scoble and some other commenters getting blocked, according to a company spokesperson.\n\nUsers attempting to comment on blog posts have recently been prevented from doing so, with warning text from the company saying that \"this comment can\'t be posted\" because it is \"irrelevant or inappropriate.\" We\'ve heard back from Facebook, and here\'s what it says has been going on.',1,'2012-05-05 16:22:22','Josh Constine'),(220,1,'83b9c536d52b8a596a34a72b9a2eecd3','http://techcrunch.com/?p=546422','2012-05-06 10:54:35','Chain-Link Confidentiality: A HIPAA-Like Approach To Online Privacy','http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/TgKWPWfd2Z4/','','<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/chain_link_links.jpg?w=100&amp;h=70&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"chain_link_links\" />As we put more of our private information online and entrust it to web services, privacy breaches become almost inevitable. One major problem with online privacy is that there is really noÃ‚Â enforceableÃ‚Â chain of confidentiality. So when a third-party service makes your information available to another party, things can get complicated. A <a href=\"http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2045818\">new paper</a> by Samford University law professor Woodrow Harzog argues that traditional privacy laws aren\'t the best ways to protect private information online. Instead, he suggests an approach that more like the U.S. <a href=\"http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/\">HIPAA rules</a>Ã‚Â that currently govern how private health information can be shared between your health provider and third parties. The system he proposes would be based on established principles inÃ‚Â confidentialityÃ‚Â and contract law.\n',1,'2012-05-05 16:00:44','Frederic Lardinois'),(222,3,'30bdb131095ed770f9edf07deaf923aa','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16675','2012-05-06 10:54:37','Impressed','http://www.manystuff.org/?p=16675','','<p><a href=\"http://www.parcsaintleger.fr/popups-prog-hlm-2012/impressed.htm\"><img src=\"http://www.manystuff.org/wp-content/uploa